00:02:52.370 --> 00:02:55.340
So pretty cool.

00:02:55.340 --> 00:02:58.360
I'm going to try here to put
an awful lot of stuff in here,

00:02:58.360 --> 00:03:00.800
and since I'm not really
quite sure what backgrounds

00:03:00.800 --> 00:03:03.620
are out here today, I'm going to
try not to be boring and throw

00:03:03.620 --> 00:03:05.630
a little bit in for everything.

00:03:05.630 --> 00:03:10.555
I'm going to start with
a slide after this one.

00:03:10.555 --> 00:03:12.430
There was a series of
talks at the MIT Museum

00:03:12.430 --> 00:03:15.700
a few years back called
Life in the Universe,

00:03:15.700 --> 00:03:20.590
and the last talk was on finding
them, and the one before that,

00:03:20.590 --> 00:03:24.567
I went to just to see what kind
of people go to these things.

00:03:24.567 --> 00:03:26.400
And one of the questions
during that session

00:03:26.400 --> 00:03:30.580
was something like
this-- I've heard

00:03:30.580 --> 00:03:33.590
that spy satellites can read
license plates down on Earth

00:03:33.590 --> 00:03:34.310
here.

00:03:34.310 --> 00:03:37.620
Can't we just do that on
planets around other stars?

00:03:37.620 --> 00:03:41.084
And the guy who was
talking said, well,

00:03:41.084 --> 00:03:42.750
I think that's a
question for next time.

00:03:42.750 --> 00:03:44.020
Well, next time
was my time, so I

00:03:44.020 --> 00:03:45.311
decided I'd start with a slide.

00:03:45.311 --> 00:03:47.340
So here's the slide,
which is well,

00:03:47.340 --> 00:03:49.512
what about the
license plate myth,

00:03:49.512 --> 00:03:50.720
and what about other planets?

00:03:50.720 --> 00:03:53.230
So here's the deal.

00:03:53.230 --> 00:03:56.060
You can just do a basic
optical calculation, which

00:03:56.060 --> 00:03:59.610
is look at diffraction limited
resolution looking down,

00:03:59.610 --> 00:04:02.570
but turn the Hubble in the wrong
direction, programming error.

00:04:02.570 --> 00:04:04.580
You're probably running
Windows or something,

00:04:04.580 --> 00:04:07.610
and if you take the actual
parameters of the Hubble,

00:04:07.610 --> 00:04:09.940
fly it a little low,
about 100 miles,

00:04:09.940 --> 00:04:12.430
and just look at what the
diffraction limited resolution

00:04:12.430 --> 00:04:12.930
is.

00:04:12.930 --> 00:04:14.580
It's about 1.6
inches, so you could

00:04:14.580 --> 00:04:16.379
reach large license plates.

00:04:16.379 --> 00:04:18.670
Of course, license plates
are on the back side of cars,

00:04:18.670 --> 00:04:20.670
so if you're looking straight
down, you wouldn't see it.

00:04:20.670 --> 00:04:22.150
You'd have to put the
license plate on the top,

00:04:22.150 --> 00:04:23.733
but anyway, the
number is about right.

00:04:23.733 --> 00:04:27.800
But then what about doing
this on other planets?

00:04:27.800 --> 00:04:31.100
Well, let's go for some
serious distance here.

00:04:31.100 --> 00:04:33.684
Let's try a planet around a
star about 25 light years away.

00:04:33.684 --> 00:04:35.850
That's far enough out to
have some reasonable number

00:04:35.850 --> 00:04:39.090
of candidates for
habitable planets.

00:04:39.090 --> 00:04:42.540
And the good news
is that there's

00:04:42.540 --> 00:04:43.832
no problem with the brightness.

00:04:43.832 --> 00:04:45.331
You might think,
well, far away, you

00:04:45.331 --> 00:04:46.570
don't have very many photons.

00:04:46.570 --> 00:04:50.349
But that's not the
problem, because you

00:04:50.349 --> 00:04:51.890
have to use a bigger
telescope to get

00:04:51.890 --> 00:04:53.450
the same diffraction
limited resolution,

00:04:53.450 --> 00:04:55.408
and that's going to scale
up like the distance.

00:04:55.408 --> 00:04:59.560
So when you scale up the
telescope proportional

00:04:59.560 --> 00:05:04.860
to the distance, then to
keep the same resolution

00:05:04.860 --> 00:05:06.440
in the collecting area goes up.

00:05:06.440 --> 00:05:08.410
It can square the
distance, and that exactly

00:05:08.410 --> 00:05:09.980
compensates for the
falloff of light, which

00:05:09.980 --> 00:05:11.110
is the square of distance.

00:05:11.110 --> 00:05:12.443
So you've got plenty of photons.

00:05:12.443 --> 00:05:13.010
No prob.

00:05:13.010 --> 00:05:15.160
The prob is you need
kind of a big telescope,

00:05:15.160 --> 00:05:17.000
and here's how big it is.

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:21.000
It works out to be about 18 AU.

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:24.230
18 AU is the mean distance
of Earth from sun.

00:05:24.230 --> 00:05:27.450
And so I made a little
scale model here.

00:05:27.450 --> 00:05:31.610
There's an antenna that's about
the size of Saturn's orbit.

00:05:31.610 --> 00:05:34.920
Kind of big, and I people
don't make optical telescopes

00:05:34.920 --> 00:05:37.650
that big, so I just stole a
radio telescope picture here.

00:05:37.650 --> 00:05:40.110
But the other thing is it
has to be kind of accurate,

00:05:40.110 --> 00:05:42.860
because this is light, and it
has to be diffraction limited,

00:05:42.860 --> 00:05:46.032
so it has to be accurate
to better than 1/20

00:05:46.032 --> 00:05:48.240
of a wavelength of light
works out to be about 1/1000

00:05:48.240 --> 00:05:49.550
the diameter of a human hair.

00:05:49.550 --> 00:05:53.370
This is an interesting antenna.

00:05:53.370 --> 00:05:56.150
But then you think, OK, if
they have license plates,

00:05:56.150 --> 00:05:57.940
then they have cars,
and they have laws,

00:05:57.940 --> 00:05:59.650
and that means they have police.

00:05:59.650 --> 00:06:02.120
And that means they
have police radios,

00:06:02.120 --> 00:06:03.540
so they know about radios.

00:06:03.540 --> 00:06:05.290
So they know what
radio communication.

00:06:05.290 --> 00:06:07.822
Why don't we just ask
them what the license

00:06:07.822 --> 00:06:10.280
plates look like instead of
doing this kind of crazy thing?

00:06:10.280 --> 00:06:12.720
So that gets into the whole
business of communication

00:06:12.720 --> 00:06:13.970
over these distances.

00:06:13.970 --> 00:06:15.250
So here's a nerdy slide.

00:06:15.250 --> 00:06:18.616
Some of these slides are
sort of warning away nerds,

00:06:18.616 --> 00:06:20.740
but you guys are nerds, so
there's no problem here.

00:06:20.740 --> 00:06:22.420
So here's the question.

00:06:22.420 --> 00:06:24.460
Can you communicate
over these distances?

00:06:24.460 --> 00:06:26.170
And you might start
with-- by the way,

00:06:26.170 --> 00:06:27.590
I'm not a PowerPoint guy.

00:06:27.590 --> 00:06:29.760
Maybe you can tell.

00:06:29.760 --> 00:06:31.494
But I did learn
about the animation,

00:06:31.494 --> 00:06:33.910
but all I could figure was you
could fly in from the left.

00:06:33.910 --> 00:06:36.600
So a lot of stuff
flies in from the left.

00:06:36.600 --> 00:06:38.420
Sorry about that.

00:06:38.420 --> 00:06:40.900
So take a couple of modest
sized digits, 300 meters.

00:06:40.900 --> 00:06:45.384
That's the size of the Arecibo
great dish down in Puerto Rico.

00:06:45.384 --> 00:06:46.800
Put these things
a modest distance

00:06:46.800 --> 00:06:48.222
apart like 1,000 light years.

00:06:48.222 --> 00:06:49.680
Within 1,000 light
years, there are

00:06:49.680 --> 00:06:52.560
about a million sun-like stars,
so this is a reasonable piece

00:06:52.560 --> 00:06:53.540
of the galaxy.

00:06:53.540 --> 00:06:56.240
It's about the thickness of
the galaxy out where we live.

00:06:56.240 --> 00:07:01.590
And transmit $1 worth of
electrical energy converted

00:07:01.590 --> 00:07:02.990
into radio waves.

00:07:02.990 --> 00:07:04.590
So here's the thing
called a nerd box,

00:07:04.590 --> 00:07:07.106
and the nerd box
simply calculates

00:07:07.106 --> 00:07:08.730
how much energy will
be received if you

00:07:08.730 --> 00:07:11.510
transmit $1 worth with the
fraction limited antennas

00:07:11.510 --> 00:07:12.690
of this size.

00:07:12.690 --> 00:07:15.130
And it works out to be about
2 times n minus 11 ergs when

00:07:15.130 --> 00:07:16.380
you scratch through the thing.

00:07:16.380 --> 00:07:18.060
By the way, the antenna has
quite a lot of gain there.

00:07:18.060 --> 00:07:20.490
I just marked in there
it's about 90 db of gain,

00:07:20.490 --> 00:07:21.910
factor of 10 to the ninth.

00:07:21.910 --> 00:07:23.260
So that helps a lot.

00:07:23.260 --> 00:07:26.340
Big antennas, short
wavelength-- that's good.

00:07:26.340 --> 00:07:27.990
But what's 10 the minus 11 ergs?

00:07:27.990 --> 00:07:29.090
What does it compete with?

00:07:29.090 --> 00:07:31.220
Well, it competes with
background-- oh, yeah, you've

00:07:31.220 --> 00:07:32.928
got to have the little
thing here, again,

00:07:32.928 --> 00:07:35.064
for the regular
audience, which is

00:07:35.064 --> 00:07:37.230
when you get to the punchline,
that's the good part.

00:07:37.230 --> 00:07:39.260
This is one of those
Sid Harris cartoons

00:07:39.260 --> 00:07:42.310
used without permission here.

00:07:42.310 --> 00:07:45.040
This works out to be
about a trillionth

00:07:45.040 --> 00:07:46.740
the energy of a
falling snowflake,

00:07:46.740 --> 00:07:48.670
so it's not a lot
of energy there.

00:07:48.670 --> 00:07:51.470
But it competes with even
smaller background numbers,

00:07:51.470 --> 00:07:53.130
which is thermal noise.

00:07:53.130 --> 00:07:54.642
And at these kinds
of wavelengths,

00:07:54.642 --> 00:07:56.100
you can achieve
system temperatures

00:07:56.100 --> 00:07:58.650
of 25 Kelvins or even
less, or about 10

00:07:58.650 --> 00:08:01.350
to the minus 15 ergs, a few
times 10 to the minus 15.

00:08:01.350 --> 00:08:02.990
So in other words,
the receive signals

00:08:02.990 --> 00:08:04.940
about 10,000 times noise.

00:08:04.940 --> 00:08:05.590
No problem.

00:08:05.590 --> 00:08:07.506
In fact, you could chop
it up into little bits

00:08:07.506 --> 00:08:09.570
and send a whole bunch of bytes.

00:08:09.570 --> 00:08:12.950
So interstellar
telegrams are cheap.

00:08:12.950 --> 00:08:15.400
Here's, again, the same
diagram, and they cost something

00:08:15.400 --> 00:08:17.360
like half a cent per word.

00:08:17.360 --> 00:08:19.920
This is a calculation
originally that I

00:08:19.920 --> 00:08:21.770
saw from a wonderful
professor at Harvard

00:08:21.770 --> 00:08:23.060
by the name of Ed Purcell.

00:08:23.060 --> 00:08:25.850
Perhaps, some of you
know his E&amp;M book.

00:08:25.850 --> 00:08:28.330
Anyway, that sounds good.

00:08:28.330 --> 00:08:29.280
What's coming next?

00:08:29.280 --> 00:08:31.154
I guess what's
coming next is OK,

00:08:31.154 --> 00:08:33.070
but what's out there
within 1,000 light years?

00:08:33.070 --> 00:08:34.840
And here's a little
picture of the galaxy.

00:08:34.840 --> 00:08:36.715
It's kind of a flat
thing with lots of stars.

00:08:36.715 --> 00:08:37.270
Some are red.

00:08:37.270 --> 00:08:38.190
Some are blue.

00:08:38.190 --> 00:08:40.590
There we are out in the--
does this pointer work?

00:08:40.590 --> 00:08:41.940
Oh, this pointer works.

00:08:41.940 --> 00:08:43.980
Can you see that?

00:08:43.980 --> 00:08:46.330
Here we are, sort of in
the galactic suburbs.

00:08:46.330 --> 00:08:49.120
And in the immediate
region where we are,

00:08:49.120 --> 00:08:50.700
the galaxy is about
1,000 light years

00:08:50.700 --> 00:08:53.490
in thickness from where most
of the stars are in the disk,

00:08:53.490 --> 00:08:56.340
and there's about a million like
the sun number I made before.

00:08:56.340 --> 00:08:59.590
So there's plenty of
candidates, and as we

00:08:59.590 --> 00:09:04.420
know from recent exoplanet
searches, experiments,

00:09:04.420 --> 00:09:08.820
things like Kepler, and so
on, most stars have planets,

00:09:08.820 --> 00:09:11.190
and probably 20% of them
have Earth-like planets--

00:09:11.190 --> 00:09:12.780
inhabitable.

00:09:12.780 --> 00:09:15.100
Maybe 10% or 20% habitable
Earth-like planets.

00:09:15.100 --> 00:09:17.320
It's an amazing number.

00:09:17.320 --> 00:09:18.940
20 years ago, nobody knew that.

00:09:18.940 --> 00:09:21.570
In fact, nobody had any examples
of planetary systems anywhere

00:09:21.570 --> 00:09:25.330
except here and one
weirdo with pulsars.

00:09:25.330 --> 00:09:26.140
What's this say?

00:09:26.140 --> 00:09:29.340
Oh, yeah, and if you're worried
that that's not the stars--

00:09:29.340 --> 00:09:31.340
I don't know why
you'd worry-- there's

00:09:31.340 --> 00:09:33.720
10 to the 11th galaxies.

00:09:33.720 --> 00:09:36.380
The only problem is there's
that pesky speed of light thing,

00:09:36.380 --> 00:09:38.250
so they may be out
there, but it's

00:09:38.250 --> 00:09:43.271
kind of annoyingly long
round-trip latency.

00:09:43.271 --> 00:09:45.020
If you want one of
these gee whiz numbers,

00:09:45.020 --> 00:09:45.910
here's the gee whiz number.

00:09:45.910 --> 00:09:47.910
There are more stars in
the universe than grains

00:09:47.910 --> 00:09:50.220
of sand on all beaches of
Earth, and I can say this

00:09:50.220 --> 00:09:52.300
with some authority having
done the back of the envelope

00:09:52.300 --> 00:09:54.383
calculation, which was
just flew in from the left.

00:09:57.020 --> 00:09:59.370
And what I did was I was
generous with my beaches.

00:09:59.370 --> 00:10:02.460
I let there be 100,000
kilometers of beaches.

00:10:05.360 --> 00:10:08.070
Shorelines are fractal kind
of, and they zigzag in and out.

00:10:08.070 --> 00:10:10.580
I gave these things
100 meters of depth.

00:10:10.580 --> 00:10:13.710
That's a pretty good beach,
and toward the water--

00:10:13.710 --> 00:10:14.590
30 feet deep.

00:10:14.590 --> 00:10:15.560
Not bad, huh?

00:10:15.560 --> 00:10:18.340
So there's 10 to the 11th
cubic meters of beach,

00:10:18.340 --> 00:10:22.360
and I gave sand a half
a millimeter cubed.

00:10:22.360 --> 00:10:24.630
That's about 10 minus
10 cubic meters,

00:10:24.630 --> 00:10:26.270
so you get 10 to the
21 grains of sand,

00:10:26.270 --> 00:10:29.370
but there's 10 to the 22 stars
at least in the universe.

00:10:29.370 --> 00:10:32.260
So there you go.

00:10:32.260 --> 00:10:35.690
This is done on the back of
a crane's beautiful envelope,

00:10:35.690 --> 00:10:38.070
and I showed this
thing at a conference

00:10:38.070 --> 00:10:39.770
called EG in California.

00:10:39.770 --> 00:10:42.230
A whole bunch of very
interesting people go to that,

00:10:42.230 --> 00:10:44.917
and one of them is
the MythBuster guy,

00:10:44.917 --> 00:10:46.000
the guy with the red hair.

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:47.660
What's his name?

00:10:47.660 --> 00:10:48.302
Adam Savage.

00:10:48.302 --> 00:10:50.260
And he said afterward,
he looked at this thing.

00:10:50.260 --> 00:10:52.510
He said, I've got to
have that envelope.

00:10:52.510 --> 00:10:54.230
He said, send it to me.

00:10:54.230 --> 00:10:55.950
I'll send you
something really cool.

00:10:55.950 --> 00:10:58.070
So I mailed the actual envelope.

00:10:58.070 --> 00:11:01.506
This is all I have left, and
he never sent me anything.

00:11:01.506 --> 00:11:05.630
So Adam Savage.

00:11:05.630 --> 00:11:07.200
OK.

00:11:07.200 --> 00:11:08.950
So planets-- how do
you find planets?

00:11:08.950 --> 00:11:12.180
Well, people have been
finding planets like crazy

00:11:12.180 --> 00:11:13.067
in the last decade.

00:11:13.067 --> 00:11:15.150
One way to do it, the first
way that really worked

00:11:15.150 --> 00:11:16.040
was spectroscopic.

00:11:16.040 --> 00:11:18.660
You look at the spectral
lines of a star,

00:11:18.660 --> 00:11:20.720
and the recoil kind
of going around

00:11:20.720 --> 00:11:24.360
gives you a Doppler shift,
periodic Doppler shift.

00:11:24.360 --> 00:11:25.620
It's not so easy to do.

00:11:25.620 --> 00:11:27.090
There's turbulence on the star.

00:11:27.090 --> 00:11:29.067
You have to do this
very precisely.

00:11:29.067 --> 00:11:31.150
They threw an [INAUDIBLE]
absorption cell in there

00:11:31.150 --> 00:11:33.100
to give calibrated lines
to sort of compensate

00:11:33.100 --> 00:11:34.539
for everything that goes wrong.

00:11:34.539 --> 00:11:36.580
And then you look at the
Doppler shift over time,

00:11:36.580 --> 00:11:39.570
and here's an example
of a pretty heavy planet

00:11:39.570 --> 00:11:42.440
and a pretty slow orbit
around another star.

00:11:42.440 --> 00:11:46.140
You see this one has been going
on for about 10 or 12 years.

00:11:46.140 --> 00:11:47.900
You see about one full cycle.

00:11:47.900 --> 00:11:49.830
So this is the radial
velocity method.

00:11:49.830 --> 00:11:52.820
It has a strong bias
toward heavy close

00:11:52.820 --> 00:11:54.840
in planets, close in
because it goes rapidly,

00:11:54.840 --> 00:11:56.280
and you get to see
several cycles.

00:11:56.280 --> 00:11:59.650
Heavy, because you get
a big recoil velocity.

00:11:59.650 --> 00:12:01.830
Actually, the close in also
gives you more velocity.

00:12:01.830 --> 00:12:05.172
So what it tends to
favor, heavy close in.

00:12:05.172 --> 00:12:07.380
That is hot Jupiters, and
the very first planet found

00:12:07.380 --> 00:12:09.850
was that the Jupiter
in a several-day orbit.

00:12:09.850 --> 00:12:10.900
Completely unexpected.

00:12:10.900 --> 00:12:12.570
We don't have those things here.

00:12:12.570 --> 00:12:14.610
And so people start
to wonder, do we

00:12:14.610 --> 00:12:16.330
live in the weird
planetary system?

00:12:16.330 --> 00:12:19.140
In fact, the whole universe
out there is hot Jupiters.

00:12:19.140 --> 00:12:21.410
But no, it's really
a selection effect,

00:12:21.410 --> 00:12:25.430
and when you do more
careful measurements

00:12:25.430 --> 00:12:29.550
and try to dig down into the
harder to detect planets,

00:12:29.550 --> 00:12:31.930
you actually find that
Earth-like planets

00:12:31.930 --> 00:12:32.680
are rather common.

00:12:32.680 --> 00:12:34.090
Now I have a little
bit of stuff on this.

00:12:34.090 --> 00:12:34.600
Let's see.

00:12:34.600 --> 00:12:37.470
Here's a graph that was
put together, actually

00:12:37.470 --> 00:12:40.580
by a former student
of mine in SETI,

00:12:40.580 --> 00:12:44.970
and he's become a big stick
in the business of Exo-Earth.

00:12:44.970 --> 00:12:47.050
And looking at a
bunch of stuff, this

00:12:47.050 --> 00:12:48.550
was the radial
velocity measurements

00:12:48.550 --> 00:12:50.800
and the spectroscopic
thing that I just showed.

00:12:50.800 --> 00:12:52.890
The fact is that-- and
what he's plotting here

00:12:52.890 --> 00:12:57.560
is mass here or minimum mass,
because it depends on-- all

00:12:57.560 --> 00:13:00.280
you can see is what-- if
the thing is inclined,

00:13:00.280 --> 00:13:04.909
then you only get the
trigonometric projection

00:13:04.909 --> 00:13:05.450
of the thing.

00:13:05.450 --> 00:13:09.250
But here would be an
Earth mass down here.

00:13:09.250 --> 00:13:11.770
And what you see, this
part here that's all blue

00:13:11.770 --> 00:13:14.160
is basically the search
is incomplete down there.

00:13:14.160 --> 00:13:17.290
In fact, it's 0% complete,
because it's really hard

00:13:17.290 --> 00:13:19.760
to see slow light planets.

00:13:19.760 --> 00:13:21.470
But you could take
what you have here

00:13:21.470 --> 00:13:23.630
and extrapolate based
on the incompleteness,

00:13:23.630 --> 00:13:26.760
and from that, you can get a
measure of what's down there.

00:13:26.760 --> 00:13:29.987
And from extrapolation, which
is admittedly a bit hazardous,

00:13:29.987 --> 00:13:32.070
you get something like a
quarter of sun-like stars

00:13:32.070 --> 00:13:37.230
harbor a close in planet
of Earth-like mass.

00:13:37.230 --> 00:13:39.730
So more recently,
this other technique,

00:13:39.730 --> 00:13:42.810
which is of transits, so a
planet goes in front of a star,

00:13:42.810 --> 00:13:44.852
and if we happen to be in
the plane of the orbit,

00:13:44.852 --> 00:13:47.059
then we're going to see a
little dimming of the star.

00:13:47.059 --> 00:13:47.590
Not much.

00:13:47.590 --> 00:13:49.090
Look at the scale
on the left there.

00:13:49.090 --> 00:13:53.094
So we're seeing five
parts in 10,000,

00:13:53.094 --> 00:13:54.260
and that's a pretty big one.

00:13:54.260 --> 00:13:55.560
And you get this
periodic, and this

00:13:55.560 --> 00:13:57.518
is a star with a period
of, I don't know, looks

00:13:57.518 --> 00:14:01.200
