00:16:28.130 --> 00:16:29.430
Are they as smart as we are?

00:16:29.430 --> 00:16:32.280
Are they as smart
people at Google?

00:16:32.280 --> 00:16:35.189
So let me just show you
my little timeline thing.

00:16:35.189 --> 00:16:36.980
Astronomers love to do
this kind of stuff--

00:16:36.980 --> 00:16:39.090
give you the astronomical
perspective, which

00:16:39.090 --> 00:16:41.590
is everything you know, everyone
you know is the thinnest

00:16:41.590 --> 00:16:42.804
slice of time possible.

00:16:42.804 --> 00:16:44.720
I think for you guys,
this is kind of obvious,

00:16:44.720 --> 00:16:45.720
but anyway, here we are.

00:16:45.720 --> 00:16:50.030
Big Bang-- Earth's sun
and the whole solar system

00:16:50.030 --> 00:16:52.950
formed about four and
1/2 billion years ago.

00:16:52.950 --> 00:16:54.750
And what we do is
expand that to one day.

00:16:54.750 --> 00:16:56.840
So if we call that
one day, we can

00:16:56.840 --> 00:16:58.800
talk about when events
happened in this day.

00:16:58.800 --> 00:17:01.550
The day started when the Sun and
Earth were born, approximately.

00:17:01.550 --> 00:17:03.030
So life arises early on Earth.

00:17:03.030 --> 00:17:05.125
Look at that-- 5:00
in the morning.

00:17:05.125 --> 00:17:06.660
The Sun wasn't even up yet.

00:17:06.660 --> 00:17:10.540
Well, that's a bit
of a mixed metaphor.

00:17:10.540 --> 00:17:12.589
But life didn't get
interesting until a few hours

00:17:12.589 --> 00:17:15.880
before midnight, so now
we'll expand that last hour.

00:17:15.880 --> 00:17:17.319
Here we are at the last hour.

00:17:17.319 --> 00:17:20.730
Dinosaurs went extinct about
20 minutes before midnight.

00:17:20.730 --> 00:17:22.490
That's 65 million years ago.

00:17:22.490 --> 00:17:23.460
So where's the action?

00:17:23.460 --> 00:17:28.350
Well, the action's really in the
last minute, the last minute.

00:17:28.350 --> 00:17:28.850
Let's see.

00:17:28.850 --> 00:17:31.350
A minute is-- well, it's
50,000 years per second,

00:17:31.350 --> 00:17:33.140
so you can figure this out.

00:17:33.140 --> 00:17:35.300
It's a few million years.

00:17:35.300 --> 00:17:37.900
Here's the Neanderthals.

00:17:37.900 --> 00:17:40.162
That was about
100,000 years ago.

00:17:40.162 --> 00:17:42.620
Maybe things were happening
here, but not very interesting.

00:17:42.620 --> 00:17:45.490
Certainly not for
Google kind of interest.

00:17:45.490 --> 00:17:49.364
So let's take the last second,
so a second is 50,000 years.

00:17:49.364 --> 00:17:50.780
Now things are
starting to happen.

00:17:50.780 --> 00:17:53.770
10,000 years ago-- agriculture.

00:17:53.770 --> 00:17:55.770
And recorded history
basically 5,000 years ago,

00:17:55.770 --> 00:17:56.394
but look at it.

00:17:56.394 --> 00:17:58.817
It's a tenth of a
second before midnight.

00:17:58.817 --> 00:18:00.400
Does that give you
an interesting idea

00:18:00.400 --> 00:18:03.890
of the compression of time or
expansion of time or whatever?

00:18:03.890 --> 00:18:07.440
Anyway, let's take the
last tenth of a second.

00:18:07.440 --> 00:18:09.700
Now things are happening.

00:18:09.700 --> 00:18:11.440
Here's Jesus, and
here's Columbus.

00:18:11.440 --> 00:18:12.550
And here's the
American Revolution,

00:18:12.550 --> 00:18:14.299
but it's sort of getting
squeezed in here.

00:18:14.299 --> 00:18:16.900
Marconi was two milliseconds
before midnight.

00:18:16.900 --> 00:18:19.480
And lasers and radio
telescopes and all the stuff

00:18:19.480 --> 00:18:21.030
that we think you
need to communicate

00:18:21.030 --> 00:18:23.682
is one millisecond
before midnight.

00:18:23.682 --> 00:18:25.140
I don't have any
more milliseconds,

00:18:25.140 --> 00:18:30.780
but 20 microseconds
is a Moore law factor

00:18:30.780 --> 00:18:34.120
of two doubly on this scale.

00:18:34.120 --> 00:18:38.060
And our timeline
for technical people

00:18:38.060 --> 00:18:40.760
is one or two years,
everything changes.

00:18:40.760 --> 00:18:44.230
How's your 10-year-old
laptop doing?

00:18:44.230 --> 00:18:51.010
So what's the takeaway
besides this is totally cool?

00:18:51.010 --> 00:18:53.770
I think the takeaway is if
we find anybody out there,

00:18:53.770 --> 00:18:55.880
and if they can
communicate at all,

00:18:55.880 --> 00:18:59.089
they're going to be in this
little millisecond just barely.

00:18:59.089 --> 00:19:00.880
But they can be anywhere
to the right where

00:19:00.880 --> 00:19:02.999
the question mark here is.

00:19:02.999 --> 00:19:04.790
In other words, anybody
we communicate with

00:19:04.790 --> 00:19:08.600
is-- anyone out there is
either incredibly dumb,

00:19:08.600 --> 00:19:11.390
or they're so advanced that
they're going to blow us away.

00:19:11.390 --> 00:19:13.972
And so in fact, if you ask
what should we be looking for,

00:19:13.972 --> 00:19:15.930
