doing the transmitting.

00:21:55.550 --> 00:21:57.010
Remember, they're
smarter than us.

00:21:57.010 --> 00:21:58.050
We're not going to
do the hard work.

00:21:58.050 --> 00:21:59.466
We're just going
to look for this.

00:21:59.466 --> 00:22:01.240
So here they are,
and they shine it out

00:22:01.240 --> 00:22:03.550
with a Keck-type
telescope, and they send

00:22:03.550 --> 00:22:04.990
this diffraction limited beam.

00:22:04.990 --> 00:22:07.584
And here we look with our
Keck, and assuming they only

00:22:07.584 --> 00:22:09.000
have 10-meter
telescopes is really

00:22:09.000 --> 00:22:10.350
a very conservative assumption.

00:22:10.350 --> 00:22:12.084
These guys are good.

00:22:12.084 --> 00:22:13.250
Anyway, here's what you get.

00:22:13.250 --> 00:22:14.130
You get lots of equations.

00:22:14.130 --> 00:22:14.880
You count photons.

00:22:14.880 --> 00:22:17.170
You fiddle around, even
throw in some reality

00:22:17.170 --> 00:22:21.056
here like extinction, and get
the pi squared over 16 right.

00:22:21.056 --> 00:22:23.680
There might be someone out there
who actually cares about that.

00:22:23.680 --> 00:22:26.460
And it turns out what you
get at 1,000 light years,

00:22:26.460 --> 00:22:28.490
you get about 1,000
photons per pulse,

00:22:28.490 --> 00:22:31.650
per three-nanosecond pulse.

00:22:31.650 --> 00:22:34.060
And the stellar background,
you say, what about the star?

00:22:34.060 --> 00:22:35.540
Isn't that putting out light?

00:22:35.540 --> 00:22:37.930
Sure, but in a nanosecond,
it doesn't do much.

00:22:37.930 --> 00:22:41.990
It puts out 3 times 10 to the
minus 2 photons per nanosecond.

00:22:41.990 --> 00:22:44.450
So you get about 1/10 of
a photon from the star,

00:22:44.450 --> 00:22:47.200
and you get 1,000
photons from the laser.

00:22:47.200 --> 00:22:48.230
So 10,000 to one.

00:22:48.230 --> 00:22:49.260
Not bad.

00:22:49.260 --> 00:22:52.490
And by the way, this is
independent of distance.

00:22:52.490 --> 00:22:54.127
Inverse square, inverse square.

00:22:54.127 --> 00:22:54.960
You can't beat that.

00:22:54.960 --> 00:22:56.960
So lasers are OK.

00:22:56.960 --> 00:22:57.910
Lasers are OK.

00:22:57.910 --> 00:22:59.534
So let me tell you
about some searches.

00:22:59.534 --> 00:23:01.326
Oh, a little silly slide here.

00:23:01.326 --> 00:23:02.700
You know, what
other wavelengths?

00:23:02.700 --> 00:23:04.050
Well, if you want to
do it from the ground,

00:23:04.050 --> 00:23:05.758
you've got to get
through the atmosphere.

00:23:05.758 --> 00:23:09.510
And that pretty much limits
you to the atmospheric windows.

00:23:09.510 --> 00:23:10.720
How am I doing for time here?

00:23:10.720 --> 00:23:12.553
Well, we'll just speed
up here a little bit.

00:23:12.553 --> 00:23:15.431
This is going too slow, right?

00:23:15.431 --> 00:23:17.430
There's the radio window
and the optical window.

00:23:17.430 --> 00:23:21.030
This is actually a nice
drawing done by Ed Purcell.

00:23:21.030 --> 00:23:24.330
Again, this is a wonderful
guy from Harvard.

00:23:24.330 --> 00:23:27.580
And astronomers exploit
these things with telescopes.

00:23:27.580 --> 00:23:29.550
This is the optical window.

00:23:29.550 --> 00:23:30.500
So do humans.

00:23:30.500 --> 00:23:32.170
That's why we have eyes.

00:23:32.170 --> 00:23:35.030
If the atmosphere were
opaque in the visible,

00:23:35.030 --> 00:23:37.840
it would be kind of
silly to have eyes.

00:23:37.840 --> 00:23:39.550
Nature understood that.

00:23:39.550 --> 00:23:41.800
In the radio, we build
radio telescopes.

00:23:41.800 --> 00:23:43.370
And here's our little
one at Harvard.

00:23:43.370 --> 00:23:45.090
Actually looks
bigger than Arecibo.

00:23:45.090 --> 00:23:46.450
This is Arecibo.

00:23:46.450 --> 00:23:48.020
This is 1,000 feet.

00:23:48.020 --> 00:23:49.200
This is 84-foot.

00:23:49.200 --> 00:23:49.950
This is my son.

00:23:49.950 --> 00:23:51.430
Can you see him down there?

00:23:51.430 --> 00:23:52.810
He's about six pixels high.

00:23:52.810 --> 00:23:55.220
He was six years old.

00:23:55.220 --> 00:23:57.581
He's a year per pixel.

00:23:57.581 --> 00:23:59.080
And you might ask
the question, what

00:23:59.080 --> 00:24:00.246
about the analog of the eye?

00:24:00.246 --> 00:24:02.480
Why don't humans have antennas?

00:24:02.480 --> 00:24:03.875
I don't know.

00:24:03.875 --> 00:24:05.750
I wonder if there's
other creatures that can.

00:24:05.750 --> 00:24:08.760
That could be really helpful in
a dense fog or, I don't know,

00:24:08.760 --> 00:24:11.150
in the woods where you don't
have direct line of sight.

00:24:11.150 --> 00:24:14.060
Anyway, and remember, these are
very efficient communications.

00:24:14.060 --> 00:24:15.980
A trillionth of the
energy of a snowflake

00:24:15.980 --> 00:24:19.570
gets good communication
over these distances.

00:24:19.570 --> 00:24:22.940
Here's the first detection
of radio waves in space.

00:24:22.940 --> 00:24:24.840
This is Jansky in 1931.

00:24:24.840 --> 00:24:26.800
He was working for
the Bell system.

00:24:26.800 --> 00:24:29.410
Bell system in those days
owned the telephone networks.

00:24:29.410 --> 00:24:31.220
You may not remember
back that far.

00:24:31.220 --> 00:24:33.350
When I was a kid, you
had your dial phone.

00:24:33.350 --> 00:24:35.120
It was owned by the
Bell system, and you

00:24:35.120 --> 00:24:37.790
couldn't plug your own phone
in if you could even find one.

00:24:37.790 --> 00:24:38.630
They owned it.

00:24:38.630 --> 00:24:41.030
I took one apart, but I had
to put it back together,

00:24:41.030 --> 00:24:43.480
because it was the
only phone we had.

00:24:43.480 --> 00:24:47.265
Anyway, Bell system was
also doing transatlantic

00:24:47.265 --> 00:24:49.390
communications, and there
they were getting static,

00:24:49.390 --> 00:24:50.240
and they wanted
to find out what's

00:24:50.240 --> 00:24:51.320
the origin of the static.

00:24:51.320 --> 00:24:53.140
Of course, a lot of
it was thunderstorms.

00:24:53.140 --> 00:24:55.790
But there was this irreducible
hiss in the background

00:24:55.790 --> 00:25:00.220
that Jansky noticed, and being
a smart guy, he didn't neglect.

00:25:00.220 --> 00:25:01.650
That's how penicillin was found.

00:25:01.650 --> 00:25:04.480
It was a rotten cantaloupe
in a marketplace.

00:25:04.480 --> 00:25:05.960
Turned out to be
pretty cool stuff.

00:25:05.960 --> 00:25:08.459
Not the cantaloupe, but the
fact that some of the mold

00:25:08.459 --> 00:25:10.750
wasn't growing in certain
places around the cantaloupe,

00:25:10.750 --> 00:25:13.010
and there was a little
penicillin there instead.

00:25:13.010 --> 00:25:17.410
Anyway, he noticed that this
stuff was coming every day

00:25:17.410 --> 00:25:19.040
from-- when he
pointed to this thing,

00:25:19.040 --> 00:25:21.700
it was diurnal, 24 hours.

00:25:21.700 --> 00:25:23.490
But then when he
looked more carefully,

00:25:23.490 --> 00:25:24.840
he thought maybe it was the sun.

00:25:24.840 --> 00:25:25.960
It wasn't 24 hours.

00:25:25.960 --> 00:25:31.450
It was 23 hours and 56 minutes,
so you think a day is 24 hours,

00:25:31.450 --> 00:25:32.460
don't you?

00:25:32.460 --> 00:25:32.970
Except wait.

00:25:32.970 --> 00:25:33.553
I'm at Google.

00:25:33.553 --> 00:25:36.080
You know a day is not
24 hours, don't you?

00:25:36.080 --> 00:25:37.580
You know how long
it takes the Earth

00:25:37.580 --> 00:25:40.660
to rotate once on its axis?

00:25:40.660 --> 00:25:42.170
23 hours and 56 minutes.

00:25:42.170 --> 00:25:44.670
You're fooled by the fact that
we're going around the sun,

00:25:44.670 --> 00:25:46.440
and you think the sun is in
the same place every day.

00:25:46.440 --> 00:25:47.439
But of course, it's not.

00:25:47.439 --> 00:25:48.450
We're going around it.

00:25:48.450 --> 00:25:49.731
So anyway, sidereal time.

00:25:49.731 --> 00:25:50.730
He figured that one out.

00:25:50.730 --> 00:25:51.920
He's a smart guy.

00:25:51.920 --> 00:25:54.620
This was continuum
radio waves from space.

00:25:54.620 --> 00:25:58.680
This is basically the
birth of radio astronomy.

00:25:58.680 --> 00:26:01.830
Here's a little later, a
birth of spectral line radio

00:26:01.830 --> 00:26:02.800
astronomy.

00:26:02.800 --> 00:26:05.200
This is the fourth floor
of Lyman Lab at Harvard,

00:26:05.200 --> 00:26:08.300
and this is Doc Ewan--
Harold Ewan-- with his horn

00:26:08.300 --> 00:26:11.380
antenna looking for a mission
from neutral hydrogen.

00:26:11.380 --> 00:26:12.876
This is 1951.

00:26:12.876 --> 00:26:14.500
This is what antennas
looked like then,

00:26:14.500 --> 00:26:16.377
sort of a hacked
together piece of stuff.

00:26:16.377 --> 00:26:17.960
Look at little patches
stuck in there.

00:26:17.960 --> 00:26:21.670
So this is basically
plywood with copper sheeting

00:26:21.670 --> 00:26:22.360
stuck on there.

00:26:22.360 --> 00:26:26.510
This thing here is actually
a thing that you flip over

00:26:26.510 --> 00:26:29.200
to cover the aperture,
and the reason

00:26:29.200 --> 00:26:31.549
that Doc Ewan put
that there is that he

00:26:31.549 --> 00:26:32.590
didn't used to have that.

00:26:32.590 --> 00:26:34.465
And then in a rainstorm,
it filled up the lab

00:26:34.465 --> 00:26:38.441
with water, which he referred to
as his first signal from space.

00:26:38.441 --> 00:26:39.440
So he put that thing in.

00:26:39.440 --> 00:26:41.286
Here's what it looked
like on the other side

00:26:41.286 --> 00:26:42.410
of the wall coming in here.

00:26:42.410 --> 00:26:43.980
So here's the
waveguide coming in,

00:26:43.980 --> 00:26:47.040
and it goes the whole rack of
really fancy-looking equipment.

00:26:47.040 --> 00:26:50.960
This is radio astronomy 1951
style-- leftover war surplus

00:26:50.960 --> 00:26:52.480
local oscillators,
and look, it's

00:26:52.480 --> 00:26:54.770
even got earphones
so that Jodie Foster

00:26:54.770 --> 00:26:56.630
can listen for the signal.

00:26:56.630 --> 00:26:58.514
Anyway these guys
with a $500 grant,

00:26:58.514 --> 00:26:59.930
they did this
experiment, and they

00:26:59.930 --> 00:27:02.080
found the 21-centimeter
line from hydrogen

00:27:02.080 --> 00:27:06.160
and found the whole
spectral line thing.

00:27:06.160 --> 00:27:08.880
Nine years later, the Harvard
put up the 60-foot radio

00:27:08.880 --> 00:27:09.720
telescope.

00:27:09.720 --> 00:27:11.220
This is Purcell and
Ewan, and here's

00:27:11.220 --> 00:27:15.040
the horn that had made
the 1951 discovery.

00:27:15.040 --> 00:27:17.240
And here's that same
radio telescope pedestal

00:27:17.240 --> 00:27:19.680
with a larger dish
on it, now 84-foot.

00:27:19.680 --> 00:27:22.740
Again, with my
son there is 1983.

00:27:22.740 --> 00:27:24.350
So we press this
thing into service,

00:27:24.350 --> 00:27:28.580
and I guess I should say about
1960, this is about the time

00:27:28.580 --> 00:27:31.669
that people first started
looking seriously for microwave

00:27:31.669 --> 00:27:32.460
signals from space.

00:27:32.460 --> 00:27:36.400
And here's a shot of
Frank Drake's 84-foot.

00:27:36.400 --> 00:27:39.030
Coincidentally, the
same size as our dish.

00:27:39.030 --> 00:27:41.850
And here's Frank back
then, graduate student,

00:27:41.850 --> 00:27:43.840
and looked at two stars
for a month or two

00:27:43.840 --> 00:27:45.860
with a one channel radio.

00:27:45.860 --> 00:27:49.870
It says down here at the
bottom, we turned the telescope

00:27:49.870 --> 00:27:51.980
to epsilon eridani,
and then it happened.

00:27:51.980 --> 00:27:55.540
Wham, and as Frank likes
to say, all of a sudden out

00:27:55.540 --> 00:27:58.130
of the loudspeaker came
choo-choo-choo-choo,

00:27:58.130 --> 00:28:00.250
and they said, can
it be this easy?

00:28:00.250 --> 00:28:01.570
Turns out not to be this easy.

00:28:01.570 --> 00:28:02.960
It was a satellite.

00:28:02.960 --> 00:28:04.650
Could it be a satellite in 1960?

00:28:04.650 --> 00:28:07.000
It was something that
went choo-choo-choo.

00:28:07.000 --> 00:28:08.860
It was probably radar.

00:28:08.860 --> 00:28:12.460
Anyway, here's Frank a little
later at our telescope,

00:28:12.460 --> 00:28:15.544
a little older than when we
were looking for radio signals.

00:28:15.544 --> 00:28:17.960
Let me tell you-- oh, I've got
one more thing about Frank.

00:28:17.960 --> 00:28:18.626
He's a cool guy.

00:28:18.626 --> 00:28:21.230
He visited Harvard, and
we named our servers--

00:28:21.230 --> 00:28:25.890
that thing's a server--
after SETI people.

00:28:25.890 --> 00:28:28.220
So this one's called
Frank, so we said, Frank,

00:28:28.220 --> 00:28:29.610
will you autograph Frank?

00:28:29.610 --> 00:28:32.749
He said sure, so this
is the Drake equation.

00:28:32.749 --> 00:28:34.790
How many people have heard
of the Drake equation?

00:28:34.790 --> 00:28:35.301
Yeah, good.

00:28:35.301 --> 00:28:35.800
There it is.

00:28:35.800 --> 00:28:38.060
And Frank's trying to
think, what comes next?

00:28:38.060 --> 00:28:39.710
[GIBBERISH]

00:28:39.710 --> 00:28:41.320
Frank Drake-- he's quite amused.

00:28:41.320 --> 00:28:44.105
He's never been asked
to sign a server before.

00:28:47.390 --> 00:28:50.880
So we started looking for these
spectral lines from aliens,

00:28:50.880 --> 00:28:52.910
and we wanted more than
a one-channel receiver,

00:28:52.910 --> 00:28:55.900
which is what he used
for his search in 1960.

00:28:55.900 --> 00:28:59.170
And what we needed was a Fourier
transform type technique.

00:28:59.170 --> 00:29:02.710
So here's just a little bit
of nerd history on the Fourier

00:29:02.710 --> 00:29:05.350
transform, the fast
Fourier transform, which

00:29:05.350 --> 00:29:06.600
you guys all take for granted.

00:29:06.600 --> 00:29:08.690
It wasn't always forever.

00:29:08.690 --> 00:29:11.840
In fact, it was
rediscovered in the '60s,

00:29:11.840 --> 00:29:13.550
and here's a little
piece of the story.

00:29:13.550 --> 00:29:17.550
Dick Garwin, who was
at IBM, was the midwife

00:29:17.550 --> 00:29:20.420
between Cooley and Tukey,
and he describes this thing.

00:29:20.420 --> 00:29:24.220
And Garwin mentioned
to Tukey that he

00:29:24.220 --> 00:29:26.510
was competing Fourier
transforms and asked Tukey if he

00:29:26.510 --> 00:29:27.850
had a faster way of doing it.

00:29:27.850 --> 00:29:28.770
Tukey did.

00:29:28.770 --> 00:29:30.700
He described the
essence of the FFT.

00:29:30.700 --> 00:29:33.400
Garwin came to the computing
center to get it programmed,

00:29:33.400 --> 00:29:36.200
and as Cooley puts it--
I'll read it for you,

00:29:36.200 --> 00:29:38.280
because I probably read
faster than you read.

00:29:38.280 --> 00:29:39.480
"I was new at the
computing center.

00:29:39.480 --> 00:29:40.980
I was doing some
of my own research.

00:29:40.980 --> 00:29:43.500
Since I was the only one
with nothing important to do,

00:29:43.500 --> 00:29:44.730
they gave me this
problem to work out.

00:29:44.730 --> 00:29:47.146
It looked interesting, but I
thought that what I was doing

00:29:47.146 --> 00:29:47.980
was more important.

00:29:47.980 --> 00:29:49.813
However, with a little
prodding from Garwin,

00:29:49.813 --> 00:29:52.300
I got a program out in my
spare time and gave it to him.

00:29:52.300 --> 00:29:53.460
It was his problem,
and I thought

00:29:53.460 --> 00:29:55.126
I'll hear no more
about it and went back

00:29:55.126 --> 00:29:56.926
to doing some real work.

00:29:56.926 --> 00:29:58.425
The significance
of the factor n log

00:29:58.425 --> 00:30:01.140
n versus n squared was lost
on me, since I had never had

00:30:01.140 --> 00:30:04.420
any use for Fourier transforms.

00:30:04.420 --> 00:30:07.170
The experience since then has
given me quite an education,

00:30:07.170 --> 00:30:08.190
and when I realized
what happened,

00:30:08.190 --> 00:30:10.300
I told Garwin that if he had
any more ideas like that,

00:30:10.300 --> 00:30:11.790
I would be glad to
help him out again."

00:30:11.790 --> 00:30:13.165
So it's a wonderful
little thing,

00:30:13.165 --> 00:30:16.400
and Garwin describes-- I'll
send this thing off to David,

00:30:16.400 --> 00:30:17.720
and he can forward it around.

00:30:17.720 --> 00:30:20.470
But basically what happened
was that Garwin was sitting

00:30:20.470 --> 00:30:21.940
in a boring meeting,
and he noticed

00:30:21.940 --> 00:30:23.890
Tukey doing, as he
says, doing Fourier

00:30:23.890 --> 00:30:25.534
transforms with his left hand.

00:30:25.534 --> 00:30:27.450
He doesn't say whether
Tukey was right-handed,

00:30:27.450 --> 00:30:30.270
but I think that must be the
implication that this guy was

00:30:30.270 --> 00:30:32.790
so cool, he could do Fourier
transforms with one hand.

00:30:32.790 --> 00:30:35.970
Anyway, he asked, was there
anything that he knew about it?

00:30:35.970 --> 00:30:36.852
He said, yes, indeed.

00:30:36.852 --> 00:30:37.560
And there it was.

00:30:37.560 --> 00:30:41.010
And that's how it happened.

00:30:41.010 --> 00:30:43.815
So this is the '60s.

00:30:43.815 --> 00:30:45.190
We're back with
Frank Drake here,

00:30:45.190 --> 00:30:49.130
and where do you look
for these radial lines?

00:30:49.130 --> 00:30:51.360
And Cocconi and
Morrison-- Phil Morrison

00:30:51.360 --> 00:30:54.600
from just down the street there
at MIT-- looked into this.

00:30:54.600 --> 00:30:56.000
He was at Cornell at the time.

00:30:56.000 --> 00:30:56.990
Where should you look?

00:30:56.990 --> 00:30:59.290
Well, you look at the whole
radio frequency spectrum,

00:30:59.290 --> 00:31:01.780
and electromagnetic
radiation really

00:31:01.780 --> 00:31:04.030
is the way to go, sort of
by elimination of everything

00:31:04.030 --> 00:31:05.010
else we know about.

00:31:05.010 --> 00:31:07.570
And there's this one line,
this 21-centimeter line,

00:31:07.570 --> 00:31:10.170
the thing that was discovered
by Purcell and Ewan.

00:31:10.170 --> 00:31:13.359
And it's the marker out there.

00:31:13.359 --> 00:31:14.650
It's really the place you look.

00:31:14.650 --> 00:31:17.384
So these guys suggested
that's where you should look.

00:31:17.384 --> 00:31:19.300
It also happens to be
in a pretty quiet region

00:31:19.300 --> 00:31:20.740
of the radio and noise spectrum.

00:31:20.740 --> 00:31:23.090
Here's roughly what
sky noise looks

00:31:23.090 --> 00:31:24.930
like viewed from
down on Earth, so you

00:31:24.930 --> 00:31:26.400
get these atmospheric lines.

00:31:26.400 --> 00:31:28.350
The galaxy itself
makes a lot of noise,

00:31:28.350 --> 00:31:31.570
and here's this quiet region in
the gigahertz in the microwave,

00:31:31.570 --> 00:31:32.860
centimetric microwave.

00:31:32.860 --> 00:31:34.710
So that's where people look.

00:31:34.710 --> 00:31:38.560
And now let me show you a few
experiments in the 29 minutes

00:31:38.560 --> 00:31:42.590
and 40 seconds, 39 seconds,
38 seconds remaining.

00:31:42.590 --> 00:31:47.550
So I had a sabbatical in '78
and went down to Arecibo.

00:31:47.550 --> 00:31:51.289
Actually, I wrote a letter--
remember those days--

00:31:51.289 --> 00:31:53.080
to Frank Drake saying
that was interesting.

00:31:53.080 --> 00:31:54.870
Looking for life in Puerto Rico.

00:31:54.870 --> 00:31:55.820
He got the joke.

00:31:55.820 --> 00:32:00.880
And he sent me down there, and
I built this little system here

00:32:00.880 --> 00:32:02.837
that involved-- well,
actually, Arecibo

00:32:02.837 --> 00:32:05.170
has all kinds of receiver
things, and all you have to do

00:32:05.170 --> 00:32:06.086
is plug them together.

00:32:06.086 --> 00:32:09.540
So I did real time
digitizing of what's

00:32:09.540 --> 00:32:11.990
coming in off the
antenna and recorded this

00:32:11.990 --> 00:32:15.230
all on a tape, which
then got FFTs offline.

00:32:15.230 --> 00:32:19.220
Computer wasn't fast enough
to do 64k FFTs in real time

00:32:19.220 --> 00:32:21.460
at a kilo sample per second.

00:32:21.460 --> 00:32:22.920
Can you remember those days?

00:32:22.920 --> 00:32:26.900
I mean nowadays, your smartphone
will do mega channel FFTs

00:32:26.900 --> 00:32:29.320
in real time of
anything you like.

00:32:29.320 --> 00:32:31.400
And here's this Harris computer.

00:32:31.400 --> 00:32:34.170
I remember this is a curious
computer, a 24-bit word.

00:32:34.170 --> 00:32:35.270
Isn't that weird?

00:32:35.270 --> 00:32:38.090
And it had a disk drive,
which was the size of kind

00:32:38.090 --> 00:32:39.420
of a small refrigerator.

00:32:39.420 --> 00:32:40.685
And you stuck these things in.

00:32:40.685 --> 00:32:42.800
Do you remember
those top loading--

00:32:42.800 --> 00:32:45.620
and it held 20 megabytes.

00:32:45.620 --> 00:32:46.830
Megabytes.

00:32:46.830 --> 00:32:49.830
Not gigabytes, and
definitely not terabytes.

00:32:49.830 --> 00:32:51.980
And I remember one day
going back and forth

00:32:51.980 --> 00:32:54.490
on the Pulsar, which
was the name of our bus

00:32:54.490 --> 00:32:56.110
that drove us to this place.

00:32:56.110 --> 00:32:58.110
Calculating what you could
do with 20 megabytes,

00:32:58.110 --> 00:33:01.490
you could fit most of the text
of all the books in the Library

00:33:01.490 --> 00:33:05.121
of Congress onto one of those
giant 20-megabyte multi-disk

00:33:05.121 --> 00:33:05.620
things.

00:33:05.620 --> 00:33:08.750
That was exciting days.

00:33:08.750 --> 00:33:11.030
Here's how you built a
receiver in those days.

00:33:11.030 --> 00:33:12.959
That's me, actually.

00:33:12.959 --> 00:33:14.000
You put your hard hat on.

00:33:14.000 --> 00:33:15.249
That's mostly for the picture.

00:33:15.249 --> 00:33:17.115
But you basically
built a receiver.

00:33:17.115 --> 00:33:21.070
It had racks full of things
like mixers and attenuators

00:33:21.070 --> 00:33:22.550
and power level meters.

00:33:22.550 --> 00:33:25.770
You can see those two meters
and A to D converters.

00:33:25.770 --> 00:33:27.950
And you just plug them
together with BNC cables.

00:33:27.950 --> 00:33:30.380
You sling a bunch of
them over your neck,

00:33:30.380 --> 00:33:31.590
and you just plug them in.

00:33:31.590 --> 00:33:34.120
And you do it real quick,
because your telescope time

00:33:34.120 --> 00:33:35.100
is coming up.

00:33:35.100 --> 00:33:37.800
So I did a search down there,
actually looked at 250 stars.

00:33:37.800 --> 00:33:39.610
It was actually the
most sensitive search

00:33:39.610 --> 00:33:42.756
ever done, and kept that
record for about 20 years.

00:33:42.756 --> 00:33:44.130
It was also a very
narrow search.

00:33:44.130 --> 00:33:45.920
It only looked at
about one kilohertz

00:33:45.920 --> 00:33:48.980
centered on the hydrogen line
and corrected for the Earth's

00:33:48.980 --> 00:33:51.630
motion around the sun, assuming
that the folks out there

00:33:51.630 --> 00:33:54.610
sending to us don't know
what the Earth's doing,

00:33:54.610 --> 00:33:56.480
but they know what
the sun's doing.

00:33:56.480 --> 00:33:58.685
And it exploited a
very cute little way

00:33:58.685 --> 00:34:00.060
to get rid of
interference, which

00:34:00.060 --> 00:34:03.540
is that because the Earth's
turning-- the Earth does turn--

00:34:03.540 --> 00:34:06.540
the Doppler shift along any line
of sight is changing with time.

00:34:06.540 --> 00:34:08.280
And that means that
a frequency received

00:34:08.280 --> 00:34:11.094
from an external fixed
frequency oscillator

00:34:11.094 --> 00:34:12.760
appears to be changing
with time instead

00:34:12.760 --> 00:34:14.850
of changing Doppler shift.

00:34:14.850 --> 00:34:18.449
And it changes to the tune of
about-- at the hydrogen line

00:34:18.449 --> 00:34:21.120
frequency, it's about point
0.15 hertz per second.

00:34:21.120 --> 00:34:22.790
It's actually always going down.

00:34:22.790 --> 00:34:24.726
From the time a source
rises until it sets,

00:34:24.726 --> 00:34:26.100
the frequency is
always dropping,

00:34:26.100 --> 00:34:27.725
and when it's overhead,
that's the rate

00:34:27.725 --> 00:34:28.760
at which it's dropping.

00:34:28.760 --> 00:34:33.440
So what I was doing is 60-second
integrations, which gave me

00:34:33.440 --> 00:34:35.159
a resolution of 0.015 hertz.

00:34:35.159 --> 00:34:37.489
You know how Fourier works.

00:34:37.489 --> 00:34:41.110
But a fixed frequency
signal during that time

00:34:41.110 --> 00:34:42.780
would chirp about 10 hertz.

00:34:42.780 --> 00:34:45.710
So it actually would chirp
over about 600 channels,

00:34:45.710 --> 00:34:48.620
so unless you adjust
your receiving frequency

00:34:48.620 --> 00:34:52.750
to compensate for the
acceleration on the Earth's

00:34:52.750 --> 00:34:56.936
surface, a signal from space
will seem to be chirping,

00:34:56.936 --> 00:34:58.810
and everything on Earth,
all the interference

00:34:58.810 --> 00:35:02.400
will be fixed and make a
big forest of interference.

00:35:02.400 --> 00:35:04.712
But what do you is you
chirp your receiver.

00:35:04.712 --> 00:35:05.670
It's in here somewhere.

00:35:05.670 --> 00:35:06.685
Something's chirping.

00:35:06.685 --> 00:35:07.810
Does it show some chirping?

00:35:07.810 --> 00:35:08.309
Yeah, here.

00:35:08.309 --> 00:35:11.340
See, we're programming
this first LO.

00:35:11.340 --> 00:35:12.929
Also this guy.

00:35:12.929 --> 00:35:14.720
You compensate for
that, and the only thing

00:35:14.720 --> 00:35:16.178
that'll look like
a fixed frequency

00:35:16.178 --> 00:35:17.640
is stuff coming from space.

00:35:17.640 --> 00:35:19.272
So that was a cute technique.

00:35:19.272 --> 00:35:19.980
It really worked.

00:35:19.980 --> 00:35:20.990
We didn't see anything.

00:35:20.990 --> 00:35:23.142
That's the example of
a great search here.

00:35:23.142 --> 00:35:24.100
You don't see anything.

00:35:24.100 --> 00:35:25.380
Well, anyway.

00:35:25.380 --> 00:35:30.200
What happened after this search?

00:35:30.200 --> 00:35:31.807
I took the stuff
I built from there

00:35:31.807 --> 00:35:33.890
and converted it into what
I called Suitcase SETI.

00:35:33.890 --> 00:35:36.106
This was a little
portable apparatus.

00:35:36.106 --> 00:35:37.480
I'll show you what
it looks like.

00:35:37.480 --> 00:35:38.740
It basically looked like this.

00:35:38.740 --> 00:35:43.830
This is, again,
1980s technology.

00:35:43.830 --> 00:35:45.519
Here's a dual Fourier processor.

00:35:45.519 --> 00:35:46.060
Look at that.

00:35:46.060 --> 00:35:47.450
It's a whole rack.

00:35:47.450 --> 00:35:54.050
And it's got a couple of 68,000s
cranking away doing 128k FFts,

00:35:54.050 --> 00:35:56.750
and here's a machine
actually running Unix.

00:35:56.750 --> 00:36:00.580
In 1980, that was pretty hot
stuff, portable computer.

00:36:00.580 --> 00:36:02.586
It was made by a
company called WICAT

00:36:02.586 --> 00:36:03.710
that you've never heard of.

00:36:03.710 --> 00:36:06.940
That's the World Institute
for Computer Aided Teaching.

00:36:06.940 --> 00:36:08.130
Hm?

00:36:08.130 --> 00:36:10.387
How do you know about WICAT?

00:36:10.387 --> 00:36:10.970
Did you work--

00:36:10.970 --> 00:36:12.350
AUDIENCE: The early [INAUDIBLE].

00:36:12.350 --> 00:36:13.290
PAUL HOROWITZ: Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:36:13.290 --> 00:36:14.110
So they had this machine.

00:36:14.110 --> 00:36:15.780
It only cost a few
thousand dollars,

00:36:15.780 --> 00:36:17.427
and it had a-- it was great.

00:36:17.427 --> 00:36:19.260
And here's a little
video cassette recorder.

00:36:19.260 --> 00:36:20.426
We put all our data on that.

00:36:20.426 --> 00:36:22.870
Anyway, here's the box of
the Fourier transformers.

00:36:22.870 --> 00:36:24.702
It's a bunch of 16k
memory chips here.

00:36:24.702 --> 00:36:26.410
There's a whole wire
wrapped on the back.

00:36:26.410 --> 00:36:28.120
Here's your 68,000 here.

00:36:28.120 --> 00:36:30.180
Here's a 16 by 16 multiplier.

00:36:30.180 --> 00:36:32.780
These things cost a few
hundred dollars back then.

00:36:32.780 --> 00:36:35.940
This is expensive stuff.

00:36:35.940 --> 00:36:39.151
Anyway, so Suitcase SETI
went down to Arecibo,

00:36:39.151 --> 00:36:41.150
and we looked at some
other frequencies of that.

00:36:41.150 --> 00:36:44.190
But then done with Arecibo,
came back to Harvard,

00:36:44.190 --> 00:36:46.550
and we discovered there's
this dish out there.

00:36:46.550 --> 00:36:48.920
This is in Harvard,
Massachusetts on the hillside.

00:36:48.920 --> 00:36:49.420
Or was.

00:36:49.420 --> 00:36:51.180
You can see it's kind
of pretty out there.

00:36:51.180 --> 00:36:53.638
And so what we did was we got
some money from the Planetary

00:36:53.638 --> 00:36:56.580
Society, and built the
thing called Sentinel.

00:36:56.580 --> 00:36:59.090
And we just took
this 84-foot dish

00:36:59.090 --> 00:37:00.910
and built a bunch
of RF electronics

00:37:00.910 --> 00:37:03.109
and made it look
like Arecibo to us.

00:37:03.109 --> 00:37:05.400
We had to build our own local
oscillators and all that,

00:37:05.400 --> 00:37:06.060
and here it is.

00:37:06.060 --> 00:37:09.360
And we built a system called
Sentinel and looked again

00:37:09.360 --> 00:37:10.719
at pretty narrow frequencies.

00:37:10.719 --> 00:37:12.010
Again, we didn't find anything.

00:37:12.010 --> 00:37:13.884
It has this wonderful
interference rejection.

00:37:13.884 --> 00:37:15.160
It rejects everything.

00:37:15.160 --> 00:37:16.742
You never find anything.

00:37:16.742 --> 00:37:17.700
So then what do you do?

00:37:17.700 --> 00:37:18.783
You build a bigger system.

00:37:18.783 --> 00:37:21.050
So we decided that we
needed more bandwidth.

00:37:21.050 --> 00:37:22.900
We really want to be
able to see not just

00:37:22.900 --> 00:37:25.670
signals that are corrected for
our helio center for the sun,

00:37:25.670 --> 00:37:27.940
but also for other
frames of reference

00:37:27.940 --> 00:37:31.940
like the galactic center
or the local standard rest

00:37:31.940 --> 00:37:34.650
or the cosmic background
standard of rest.

00:37:34.650 --> 00:37:36.680
So we built a
system called META.

00:37:36.680 --> 00:37:40.070
META stands for Mega Channel
Extraterrestrial Assay,

00:37:40.070 --> 00:37:42.050
and it had 8.4 million channels.

00:37:42.050 --> 00:37:45.779
And this was amazing for 19--
when was this-- about 1985.

00:37:45.779 --> 00:37:46.820
It was really impressive.

00:37:46.820 --> 00:37:47.944
There's our META processor.

00:37:47.944 --> 00:37:51.884
It had 128 68,000ths with a pile
of memory on each one and lots

00:37:51.884 --> 00:37:53.300
of block diagram-y
looking things.

00:37:53.300 --> 00:37:54.940
Here's a picture of
the control room.

00:37:54.940 --> 00:37:58.210
It's got two racks
here full of stuff,

00:37:58.210 --> 00:38:00.140
and you can't read
that, which is good,

00:38:00.140 --> 00:38:01.973
because it would be
embarrassing if you knew

00:38:01.973 --> 00:38:06.880
that it said META Supercomputer:
75 million instructions

00:38:06.880 --> 00:38:08.720
per second.

00:38:08.720 --> 00:38:11.210
You know, the Cray-1 wasn't
much faster than that.

00:38:11.210 --> 00:38:12.510
This was a supercomputer.

00:38:12.510 --> 00:38:16.262
This had 7,064k DRAM chips.

00:38:16.262 --> 00:38:17.220
I soldered them all in.

00:38:17.220 --> 00:38:18.920
I know.

00:38:18.920 --> 00:38:20.270
And they cost $3 apiece.

00:38:20.270 --> 00:38:25.250
We spent $21,000 to get
60 megabytes of memory.

00:38:25.250 --> 00:38:29.480
You can't imagine yourself in
this-- it was really like that.

00:38:29.480 --> 00:38:31.280
Anyway, so some more pictures.

00:38:31.280 --> 00:38:34.806
Here's a rack full of these
that had nine of these racks.

00:38:34.806 --> 00:38:36.430
Each one of those
has the memory on it.

00:38:36.430 --> 00:38:37.330
You can see that.

00:38:37.330 --> 00:38:38.770
And then it produced this stuff.

00:38:38.770 --> 00:38:40.690
This is, again, on
the WICAT screen,

00:38:40.690 --> 00:38:43.315
and it gave you
the whole spectrum.

00:38:43.315 --> 00:38:45.440
And then it sort of zoomed
in on the largest thing,

00:38:45.440 --> 00:38:47.023
and then it zoomed
in some more so you

00:38:47.023 --> 00:38:49.660
could see that at single
channel resolution here.

00:38:49.660 --> 00:38:51.720
And if it found
something big like this,

00:38:51.720 --> 00:38:53.940
then it put something
up on the screen,

00:38:53.940 --> 00:38:56.052
and a colleague of
mine, Bill Press,

00:38:56.052 --> 00:38:57.260
said, what's it going to say?

00:38:57.260 --> 00:38:59.570
And I said, oh, it'll say
big peak, eight sigma.

00:38:59.570 --> 00:39:01.300
And he said, no, no, no.

00:39:01.300 --> 00:39:03.360
He said, there's going
to be journalists there.

00:39:03.360 --> 00:39:04.740
Have it say
something impressive.

00:39:04.740 --> 00:39:05.490
I said, like what?

00:39:05.490 --> 00:39:09.950
Have it say, notify
operator immediately.

00:39:09.950 --> 00:39:12.320
Possible signal of
extraterrestrial origin.

00:39:12.320 --> 00:39:19.080
So there's Bill Press of
the Numerical Recipes fame.

00:39:19.080 --> 00:39:21.350
So this is what you
could do back then.

00:39:21.350 --> 00:39:22.909
It was hard work, but we did it.

00:39:22.909 --> 00:39:24.450
We didn't find
anything there either.

00:39:24.450 --> 00:39:26.570
Again, we had that same
interference rejection.

00:39:26.570 --> 00:39:29.410
I want to show you just
something about the times.

00:39:29.410 --> 00:39:32.540
So you think, oh, this
stuff seems so primitive.

00:39:32.540 --> 00:39:34.470
You can't believe that
it was hard to do.

00:39:34.470 --> 00:39:36.310
But let me just show you
