00:44:17.220 --> 00:44:19.009
Then we decided, eight
million channels.

00:44:19.009 --> 00:44:20.050
That's not nearly enough.

00:44:20.050 --> 00:44:21.734
We're not finding
anything interesting.

00:44:21.734 --> 00:44:22.650
We need more channels.

00:44:22.650 --> 00:44:25.840
So we built a thing
called beta, which

00:44:25.840 --> 00:44:28.940
is supposed to be billion
channel extraterrestrial assay.

00:44:28.940 --> 00:44:30.210
We got only 250 million.

00:44:30.210 --> 00:44:32.130
That was a lot of work
in those days, again.

00:44:32.130 --> 00:44:35.510
And the idea here was, let's
get rid of these single events

00:44:35.510 --> 00:44:37.010
that we can't pin down.

00:44:37.010 --> 00:44:39.960
We're going to have
a two-beam telescope,

00:44:39.960 --> 00:44:43.412
and because the telescope is
fixed, an east and a west beam,

00:44:43.412 --> 00:44:44.870
a source will
transit through them.

00:44:44.870 --> 00:44:47.078
So we should see it appear
first in the east and then

00:44:47.078 --> 00:44:49.150
in the west, and
just to make sure,

00:44:49.150 --> 00:44:51.300
to make it more robust
against local interference,

00:44:51.300 --> 00:44:56.090
we'll have a horizon sensitive
antenna at the top of a tower,

00:44:56.090 --> 00:44:58.780
and that'll be the veto
that's terrestrial.

00:44:58.780 --> 00:45:02.160
So we built this thing, and
here's our block diagram.

00:45:02.160 --> 00:45:05.200
You don't really care
about that, do you?

