I'll show you something
that's an even bigger garbage

00:46:13.680 --> 00:46:14.532
can coming up.

00:46:14.532 --> 00:46:16.490
So we decided to get into
the optical business,

00:46:16.490 --> 00:46:19.620
and you'll remember that
calculation, optical works.

00:46:19.620 --> 00:46:21.040
And we had this
ancient telescope.

00:46:21.040 --> 00:46:21.831
Look at this thing.

00:46:21.831 --> 00:46:22.830
Is that cool?

00:46:22.830 --> 00:46:23.920
Isn't that-- look at this.

00:46:23.920 --> 00:46:26.266
They don't build them
like that anymore.

00:46:26.266 --> 00:46:28.140
And what we did was we
tacked this little box

00:46:28.140 --> 00:46:29.890
that you see here onto
the bottom of this thing

00:46:29.890 --> 00:46:32.170
and took half of the light
out that other people were

00:46:32.170 --> 00:46:33.630
using for their experiments.

00:46:33.630 --> 00:46:36.980
And they were looking at solar
type stars for various reasons,

00:46:36.980 --> 00:46:39.730
and so we just decided we'd
take some of the signal

00:46:39.730 --> 00:46:42.690
and look for bright flashes.

00:46:42.690 --> 00:46:44.570
Here's a picture of the
little box we built.

00:46:44.570 --> 00:46:46.789
It's made out of half-inch
thick aluminum walls,

00:46:46.789 --> 00:46:48.330
because we decided
that's the easiest

00:46:48.330 --> 00:46:50.850
way to tap directly into it.

00:46:50.850 --> 00:46:53.161
And it weighed about 100 pounds.

00:46:53.161 --> 00:46:55.410
There's probably a better
way to screw things together

00:46:55.410 --> 00:46:57.534
that you don't have to make
them a half inch thick,

00:46:57.534 --> 00:47:00.070
but we were kind of-- all right.

00:47:00.070 --> 00:47:01.542
Here's a schematic.

00:47:01.542 --> 00:47:03.500
You know we do do
electronics in this business.

00:47:03.500 --> 00:47:05.570
This is sort of the
front end of this thing.

00:47:05.570 --> 00:47:07.650
We used what are called
hybrid avalanche photo

00:47:07.650 --> 00:47:11.180
detectors and a whole bunch
of other crazy stuff here.

00:47:11.180 --> 00:47:13.450
And we decided in order
to make this more robust

00:47:13.450 --> 00:47:15.420
and set up a collaboration
with Princeton,

00:47:15.420 --> 00:47:17.600
so here's our telescope,
and at Princeton, they

00:47:17.600 --> 00:47:19.900
had a 36-inch
telescope on campus.

00:47:19.900 --> 00:47:21.510
And Dave Wilkinson
basically arranged

00:47:21.510 --> 00:47:25.890
for them to build an
identical copy of our system

00:47:25.890 --> 00:47:27.770
on a somewhat smaller
telescope and to do

00:47:27.770 --> 00:47:29.380
simultaneous observations.

00:47:29.380 --> 00:47:32.100
And the nice thing
about that is that when

00:47:32.100 --> 00:47:34.160
you do simultaneous
observations,

00:47:34.160 --> 00:47:38.660
you're rather insensitive to any
local events that could produce

00:47:38.660 --> 00:47:40.580
a flashing light
at 250 miles apart,

00:47:40.580 --> 00:47:42.600
300 miles apart it says here.

00:47:42.600 --> 00:47:44.720
And better than that,
because that's about

00:47:44.720 --> 00:47:47.186
1.6 light milliseconds apart.

00:47:47.186 --> 00:47:49.060
If you're pointing some
direction in the sky,

00:47:49.060 --> 00:47:50.890
you should get your flash of
light at a different time.

00:47:50.890 --> 00:47:52.760
You know exactly when
you should get it,

00:47:52.760 --> 00:47:55.770
and we did timing with
GPS, so we could actually

00:47:55.770 --> 00:47:57.634
check to see not
only if anything ever

00:47:57.634 --> 00:47:59.550
happened at the same
time, but whether it even

00:47:59.550 --> 00:48:00.840
had the correct delay.

00:48:00.840 --> 00:48:02.630
And the result of
this was that we got

00:48:02.630 --> 00:48:04.726
basically no further events.

00:48:04.726 --> 00:48:06.350
Here's some pictures
of their telescope

00:48:06.350 --> 00:48:07.990
getting this stuff on it.

00:48:07.990 --> 00:48:10.867
We had something like a
few hundred single events

00:48:10.867 --> 00:48:12.700
before we started teaming
up with Princeton,

00:48:12.700 --> 00:48:16.810
but once we did, it drove
the event rate to zero.

00:48:16.810 --> 00:48:18.510
So here's some results.

00:48:18.510 --> 00:48:19.807
What about all this?

00:48:19.807 --> 00:48:21.890
If you don't find anything,
does it mean anything?

00:48:21.890 --> 00:48:24.431
Well, it means that the sky is
not completely full of people,

00:48:24.431 --> 00:48:29.350
of flashy things, men
in black, flashy things.

00:48:29.350 --> 00:48:31.440
But the limits are kind of weak.

00:48:31.440 --> 00:48:33.300
You can set limits of
the fraction of stars

00:48:33.300 --> 00:48:35.299
that have transmitting
civilizations that happen

00:48:35.299 --> 00:48:38.030
to be transmitting at us with
a nice bright thing at the time

00:48:38.030 --> 00:48:38.670
we're looking.

00:48:38.670 --> 00:48:40.253
So that's the kind
of numbers you get.

