but the whole sky.

00:48:49.405 --> 00:48:50.780
And this came out
of a challenge.

00:48:50.780 --> 00:48:52.440
I was on a committee
thinking about how

00:48:52.440 --> 00:48:53.890
to do SETI for
the next 20 years,

00:48:53.890 --> 00:48:56.060
and there was an optical
astronomer there,

00:48:56.060 --> 00:48:58.960
a rather famous one, who
said, of course, optical--

00:48:58.960 --> 00:49:01.777
you can't do all sky, because
you're using telescopes,

00:49:01.777 --> 00:49:03.110
and they only look at one thing.

00:49:03.110 --> 00:49:04.901
I thought that was a
really cool challenge,

00:49:04.901 --> 00:49:08.050
so I came back and said, let's
build an all sky optical SETI.

00:49:08.050 --> 00:49:09.390
So here's how you do it.

00:49:09.390 --> 00:49:11.723
You get one of these things,
and you start knocking down

00:49:11.723 --> 00:49:13.910
trees and building
and dig ditches,

00:49:13.910 --> 00:49:16.410
and you find that there's wires
in there, and then it snows.

00:49:16.410 --> 00:49:18.946
And you pour a foundation,
and then the foundation,

00:49:18.946 --> 00:49:20.070
you get this kind of thing.

00:49:20.070 --> 00:49:21.820
This is where the
telescope's going to go.

00:49:21.820 --> 00:49:23.256
And then you start
putting a roof.

00:49:23.256 --> 00:49:24.630
You make this
thing out of steel,

00:49:24.630 --> 00:49:26.419
and you put a roof on
it, and there it is.

00:49:26.419 --> 00:49:26.960
Look at that.

00:49:26.960 --> 00:49:28.709
It's got a roof, and
it goes on the rails.

00:49:28.709 --> 00:49:30.080
It's a rolloff observatory.

00:49:30.080 --> 00:49:31.380
Here comes the telescope.

00:49:31.380 --> 00:49:33.960
It was made in
Arkansas by some guys

00:49:33.960 --> 00:49:35.270
