00:54:25.930 --> 00:54:28.050
with a really clever
idea, which is this--

00:54:28.050 --> 00:54:31.525
if you take a fancy FPGA,
one of these Xilinx parts,

00:54:31.525 --> 00:54:33.150
they have a whole
bunch of inputs which

00:54:33.150 --> 00:54:34.733
are meant for digital
signals, they're

00:54:34.733 --> 00:54:36.594
LVDS differential pairs.

00:54:36.594 --> 00:54:38.010
But they're very
good comparitors,

00:54:38.010 --> 00:54:41.535
so you can trick it
into being a flash

00:54:41.535 --> 00:54:43.660
analog to digital converter,
even though it doesn't

00:54:43.660 --> 00:54:44.910
know that's what you're doing.

00:54:44.910 --> 00:54:47.770
So you tie eight of these
with a common signal,

00:54:47.770 --> 00:54:50.240
and put in a
progression of biases,

00:54:50.240 --> 00:54:51.680
and you've got yourself an ADC.

00:54:51.680 --> 00:54:53.930
And you can run these things
at 1 and 1/2 giga samples

00:54:53.930 --> 00:54:54.610
per second.

00:54:54.610 --> 00:54:57.580
And you can put 32 of
these into one chip--

00:54:57.580 --> 00:55:00.920
so he's got two pairs for the
left and right matching pixels,

00:55:00.920 --> 00:55:03.890
and then he's got 16 of those
things in one of these chips.

00:55:03.890 --> 00:55:05.390
And it's got all
kinds of other junk

00:55:05.390 --> 00:55:07.474
in here-- you know, these
chips are full of stuff.

00:55:07.474 --> 00:55:09.265
And in fact, here's
this whole little thing

00:55:09.265 --> 00:55:10.320
with this front end.

00:55:10.320 --> 00:55:13.050
It's also got-- heck you can
drop a MicroBlaze into there,

00:55:13.050 --> 00:55:14.930
and you've got an ethernet
MAC in this thing.

00:55:14.930 --> 00:55:16.860
And you name it, it's got it.

00:55:16.860 --> 00:55:22.685
So each one of these things
is a node on our network.

00:55:22.685 --> 00:55:24.060
And he put these
things together.

00:55:24.060 --> 00:55:25.435
And the damn thing
works-- here's

00:55:25.435 --> 00:55:27.670
