Whereas with the big
dishes, you can only

01:01:49.270 --> 01:01:50.930
look at a small
piece of the sky.

01:01:50.930 --> 01:01:52.350
So it actually pays to do that.

01:01:52.350 --> 01:01:54.420
Right now it costs
kind of a lot.

01:01:54.420 --> 01:01:55.920
On the other hand,
this is the stuff

01:01:55.920 --> 01:01:59.460
that gets cheaper-- the
computing and the correlating.

01:01:59.460 --> 01:02:01.250
And so really what
you should do is

01:02:01.250 --> 01:02:03.620
you should bias towards the
left side of this bar graph,

01:02:03.620 --> 01:02:04.810
and build a lot of small dishes.

01:02:04.810 --> 01:02:06.643
And that's where people
are going with this.

01:02:06.643 --> 01:02:08.520
Anyway, I would say,
in spite of all these

01:02:08.520 --> 01:02:10.650
rather stupendous
efforts, we're still

01:02:10.650 --> 01:02:14.140
in that last tenth of a
millisecond of Earth's attempt

01:02:14.140 --> 01:02:14.920
to do this right.

01:02:14.920 --> 01:02:17.700
We're still the small
fisherman in this business.

01:02:17.700 --> 01:02:20.110
And for it to succeed
at this point,

01:02:20.110 --> 01:02:22.040
we have to be
extraordinarily lucky.

01:02:22.040 --> 01:02:24.930
That's my story, thank you.

01:02:24.930 --> 01:02:26.250
[APPLAUSE]

01:02:31.990 --> 01:02:34.210
Did I leave you questionless?

01:02:34.210 --> 01:02:36.090
Impossible.

01:02:36.090 --> 01:02:37.900
AUDIENCE: So I'm
wondering-- I mean,

01:02:37.900 --> 01:02:40.700
this sort of assumes
that somebody out

01:02:40.700 --> 01:02:43.590
there has identified us as
a potentially interesting

01:02:43.590 --> 01:02:47.740
candidate, and they're
sending a pulse directed at us

01:02:47.740 --> 01:02:50.640
to see if we're listening.

01:02:50.640 --> 01:02:58.170
But what would we look
like to a civilization

01:02:58.170 --> 01:03:03.470
1,000 light years away?

01:03:03.470 --> 01:03:10.780
Like we're sending out
a bunch of RF stuff.

01:03:10.780 --> 01:03:14.050
Is it theoretically
possible for somebody

01:03:14.050 --> 01:03:20.560
to look at what a civilization
that just started emitting

01:03:20.560 --> 01:03:23.000
RF signals would look like?

01:03:23.000 --> 01:03:24.625
PAUL HOROWITZ:
Yeah, good question.

01:03:24.625 --> 01:03:26.500
So the question is,
could we detect ourselves

01:03:26.500 --> 01:03:27.791
with these kind of experiments?

01:03:27.791 --> 01:03:30.550
The answer is no, maybe from
the nearest star, but unlikely.

01:03:30.550 --> 01:03:33.190
Because the radio
signals we're creating

01:03:33.190 --> 01:03:35.760
our not intended to
establish communication.

01:03:35.760 --> 01:03:38.267
They're either piped through
pipes, or they're radars,

01:03:38.267 --> 01:03:40.600
and they're just briefly
pointed in any given direction.

01:03:40.600 --> 01:03:42.260
If they're radars,
they're broadband.

01:03:42.260 --> 01:03:46.239
If they're FM broadcasts,
they're aimed horizontally.

01:03:46.239 --> 01:03:47.280
We're doing it all wrong.

01:03:47.280 --> 01:03:50.780
But we're not looking--
maybe a sufficiently advanced

01:03:50.780 --> 01:03:53.010
civilization could
do huge antennas,

01:03:53.010 --> 01:03:54.590
and find us in our
primitive stage.

01:03:54.590 --> 01:03:56.500
We're looking for
intentional beacons.

01:03:56.500 --> 01:03:58.250
And the idea of those
first couple slides

01:03:58.250 --> 01:04:00.300
is, if we wanted to make
an intentional beacon,

01:04:00.300 --> 01:04:02.812
even with our technology,
we could do it now.

01:04:02.812 --> 01:04:04.520
But we're certainly
looking for something

01:04:04.520 --> 01:04:06.320
optimized in that way.

01:04:06.320 --> 01:04:08.110
And once it's
optimized in that way,

01:04:08.110 --> 01:04:10.970
it becomes detectable
even with our technology.

01:04:10.970 --> 01:04:12.920
But we could not detect
twin if they don't

01:04:12.920 --> 01:04:14.740
go to the effort of doing that.

01:04:14.740 --> 01:04:16.790
Some of these targets
in that breakthrough

01:04:16.790 --> 01:04:18.850
are interested in when
two planets are aligned

01:04:18.850 --> 01:04:20.225
around some other
star, might you

01:04:20.225 --> 01:04:23.400
pick up, by chance, a
communication that's

01:04:23.400 --> 01:04:24.850
between their two planets?

01:04:24.850 --> 01:04:26.891
You know, if you look at
the piece of phase space

01:04:26.891 --> 01:04:29.930
that occupies, the answer
is, what are you smoking?

01:04:29.930 --> 01:04:31.940
It's just too improbable.

01:04:31.940 --> 01:04:34.430
AUDIENCE: So are there any
efforts, or discussion,

01:04:34.430 --> 01:04:38.730
about doing things like picking
star systems with exoplanets,

01:04:38.730 --> 01:04:39.740
and--

01:04:39.740 --> 01:04:41.680
PAUL HOROWITZ: Yeah,
so somewhere in here,

01:04:41.680 --> 01:04:44.886
I had the targets-- I zipped
through at warp speed-- here's

01:04:44.886 --> 01:04:45.760
one thing to look at.

01:04:45.760 --> 01:04:48.010
Nearby stars, why not?

01:04:48.010 --> 01:04:49.020
Nice, strong signal.

01:04:49.020 --> 01:04:52.062
Some night stars--
yeah, because we

01:04:52.062 --> 01:04:53.770
know you can live
around a sun-like star,

01:04:53.770 --> 01:04:54.730
at least for awhile.

01:04:54.730 --> 01:05:00.020
Known exoplanet-- sure, but
that's a pretty small fraction.

01:05:00.020 --> 01:05:02.910
Kepler only picks up planets
that are in our plane,

01:05:02.910 --> 01:05:05.180
so it misses a lot of them.

01:05:05.180 --> 01:05:06.650
Here's this alignment thing.

01:05:06.650 --> 01:05:11.990
I think this is nut case SETI,
but there it is on the list.

01:05:11.990 --> 01:05:14.620
And a few other ideas.

01:05:14.620 --> 01:05:17.570
And the galactic plane, because
there's more demography there.

01:05:17.570 --> 01:05:21.300
And I think, also, not on this
list are other nearby galaxies.

01:05:21.300 --> 01:05:24.150
You point your
beam at Andromeda,

01:05:24.150 --> 01:05:27.455
and you pick up 10 of the
11th stars in one shot.

01:05:27.455 --> 01:05:28.830
And you might say,
oh, but that's

01:05:28.830 --> 01:05:31.626
2 million light years away.

01:05:31.626 --> 01:05:32.500
That's a weak signal.

01:05:32.500 --> 01:05:34.330
Well, think again.

01:05:34.330 --> 01:05:38.120
If Andromeda is trying
to illuminate our galaxy,

01:05:38.120 --> 01:05:40.720
they'll make a beam that
just covers our galaxy.

01:05:40.720 --> 01:05:42.610
Arrives with the same
strength as a signal

01:05:42.610 --> 01:05:44.470
of someone within our
galaxy, also trying

01:05:44.470 --> 01:05:45.794
to illuminate the whole galaxy.

01:05:45.794 --> 01:05:47.460
So it really doesn't
matter how far away

01:05:47.460 --> 01:05:51.420
you are, if you tailor your
beam to match the target size.

01:05:51.420 --> 01:05:53.900
So I think that's a perfectly
reasonable thing to do.

01:05:53.900 --> 01:05:55.380
Did that answer the question?

01:05:55.380 --> 01:05:56.670
AUDIENCE: Sure, thanks.

01:05:56.670 --> 01:05:58.180
PAUL HOROWITZ: Over there.

01:05:58.180 --> 01:06:02.210
AUDIENCE: Possibly,
sort of related-- I

01:06:02.210 --> 01:06:04.370
totally buy the concept
that we are really

01:06:04.370 --> 01:06:08.102
early on the technology side,
in a cosmic scale of time.

01:06:08.102 --> 01:06:10.560
But that's still going to be
true in 50 years, that's still

01:06:10.560 --> 01:06:12.740
going to be true in 500 years.

01:06:12.740 --> 01:06:14.360
What if everybody
feels that way?

01:06:14.360 --> 01:06:15.818
What if they're
all just listening,

01:06:15.818 --> 01:06:18.210
waiting for the other guy to
do the hard part of sending

01:06:18.210 --> 01:06:18.970
signals?

01:06:18.970 --> 01:06:22.886
PAUL HOROWITZ: Yeah, well,
I hate that question.

01:06:22.886 --> 01:06:24.275
[LAUGHTER]

01:06:25.670 --> 01:06:28.442
So I guess I'd say, ask
me again in 500 years.

01:06:28.442 --> 01:06:30.150
You know, there comes
a time in which you

01:06:30.150 --> 01:06:33.770
think you've done a thorough
scouring of receiving,

01:06:33.770 --> 01:06:35.937
given the distances and
what you know about planets.

01:06:35.937 --> 01:06:38.353
You know, we're learning an
awful lot about these planets,

01:06:38.353 --> 01:06:41.160
and I think we're going to
have much smarter searches in

01:06:41.160 --> 01:06:42.141
awhile.

01:06:42.141 --> 01:06:44.640
You'll always be able to make
an argument like that-- maybe,

01:06:44.640 --> 01:06:46.370
ultimately, we'll just decide
we're the only ones there.

01:06:46.370 --> 01:06:47.930
I find that a
completely implausible--

01:06:47.930 --> 01:06:48.550
AUDIENCE: Well, I'm
wondering if there's

01:06:48.550 --> 01:06:51.410
any sense of a technology
that you might expect

01:06:51.410 --> 01:06:53.630
to hit at some
point, where you go,

01:06:53.630 --> 01:06:56.349
oh, wow, we can
send signals now.

01:06:56.349 --> 01:06:58.640
PAUL HOROWITZ: Some people
argue we should be symmetric

01:06:58.640 --> 01:06:59.320
right now.

01:06:59.320 --> 01:07:03.660
I mean, that we only earn the
right to listen if we transmit.

01:07:03.660 --> 01:07:06.820
And I'd say, we'd be so
embarrassed with what we sent,

01:07:06.820 --> 01:07:09.060
if we do it now, because
we're so primitive.

01:07:09.060 --> 01:07:12.760
And the other thing-- so let
me just toss this idea out--

01:07:12.760 --> 01:07:14.570
when we first make
contact, it's not

01:07:14.570 --> 01:07:17.837
going to be the first
time it's ever happened.

01:07:17.837 --> 01:07:20.170
That would be astonishing--
it's happened lots of times.

01:07:20.170 --> 01:07:22.515
And in fact, if there's
sufficiently high density

01:07:22.515 --> 01:07:24.640
of such civilizations, then
they sort of a network,

01:07:24.640 --> 01:07:26.320
they have a galactic internet.

01:07:26.320 --> 01:07:29.710
They've fashioned the
ideal acquisition signal.

01:07:29.710 --> 01:07:32.049
They've done this
a million times--

01:07:32.049 --> 01:07:34.590
it's like the movie, "Contact,"
they know what they're doing.

01:07:34.590 --> 01:07:37.320
And we just go shouting in
there with a bunch of garbage

01:07:37.320 --> 01:07:40.787
and noise like
mumblings, and tell them

01:07:40.787 --> 01:07:42.620
about the wars we're
fighting, and you know,

01:07:42.620 --> 01:07:44.090
is Donald Trump going
to be the president.

01:07:44.090 --> 01:07:45.840
And they're just going
to say, oh, there's

01:07:45.840 --> 01:07:48.470
no intelligent life on Earth.

01:07:48.470 --> 01:07:49.230
[LAUGHTER]

01:07:49.230 --> 01:07:54.600
So no, I think at this point,
we definitely don't transmit.

01:07:54.600 --> 01:07:57.030
Although there are people
who say, that's wrong.

01:07:57.030 --> 01:07:58.580
There's other people who
say we shouldn't transmit,

01:07:58.580 --> 01:07:59.820
because they're going
to come and eat us.

01:07:59.820 --> 01:08:01.579
I think that's kind
of extreme, because I

01:08:01.579 --> 01:08:03.120
think if they can
actually come here,

01:08:03.120 --> 01:08:04.780
then they've grown
up enough to know

01:08:04.780 --> 01:08:06.490
not to go killing stuff off.

01:08:06.490 --> 01:08:08.830
And you can find
argument against this.

01:08:08.830 --> 01:08:14.030
But I guess I can say, in
the next few decades, I'm OK.

01:08:14.030 --> 01:08:16.399
And after that, I don't
have to worry about it,

01:08:16.399 --> 01:08:18.010
because I'm already
73 years old,

01:08:18.010 --> 01:08:21.403
and the average lifespan--
I'm pushing up against that.

01:08:21.403 --> 01:08:24.184
It's your problem.

01:08:24.184 --> 01:08:26.340
[LAUGHTER]

01:08:26.340 --> 01:08:29.962
Are there any other--
there's a question.

01:08:29.962 --> 01:08:34.569
AUDIENCE: So if there are
really advanced civilizations,

01:08:34.569 --> 01:08:36.970
like galactic scale
civilizations,

01:08:36.970 --> 01:08:40.286
do you think that looking
for pulses of light

01:08:40.286 --> 01:08:41.660
from these things
is the only way

01:08:41.660 --> 01:08:43.170
to detect such civilization?

01:08:43.170 --> 01:08:45.457
Or might there be other
things we would look for?

01:08:45.457 --> 01:08:48.040
PAUL HOROWITZ: Yeah, you have
to think about what we know now.

01:08:48.040 --> 01:08:50.123
I mean, we know that
electromagnetic communication

01:08:50.123 --> 01:08:52.500
is cool, and can do the job.

01:08:52.500 --> 01:08:53.970
If the galaxy is
really colonized,

01:08:53.970 --> 01:08:57.080
you might imagine that they
might have robotic probes that

01:08:57.080 --> 01:08:59.334
go in orbit around
likely stars, and where

01:08:59.334 --> 01:09:02.619
they'll have planets, and maybe
do some local back and forth.

01:09:02.619 --> 01:09:04.160
Wouldn't that be a
smart thing to do?

01:09:04.160 --> 01:09:07.460
People who have looked for stuff
like that haven't found it.

01:09:07.460 --> 01:09:10.270
I think if we discover new
modalities of communication,

01:09:10.270 --> 01:09:11.020
they're fair game.

01:09:11.020 --> 01:09:13.000
But from what we
know now, we don't

01:09:13.000 --> 01:09:15.238
like particles that have
mass, they go too slow,

01:09:15.238 --> 01:09:16.279
and take too much energy.

01:09:16.279 --> 01:09:17.670
We don't like charged
particles, because they

01:09:17.670 --> 01:09:19.850
bend in magnetic fields,
and they scatter.

01:09:19.850 --> 01:09:23.266
We don't like neutrinos, and
gravity waves, gravitons,

01:09:23.266 --> 01:09:25.140
because they're too hard
to make and detect--

01:09:25.140 --> 01:09:27.930
and this is certainly
decent physics.

01:09:27.930 --> 01:09:33.660
Whereas, spin one mass
zero, electromagnetic waves,

01:09:33.660 --> 01:09:35.910
just seem to have all the
right characteristics there.

01:09:35.910 --> 01:09:37.830
It works at extremely
sensitive level,

01:09:37.830 --> 01:09:39.580
and they go at the
speed of light-- that's

01:09:39.580 --> 01:09:42.361
as fast as you get to go.

01:09:42.361 --> 01:09:44.069
But we're certainly
open to other things.

01:09:44.069 --> 01:09:47.821
And if there is a
galactic network,

01:09:47.821 --> 01:09:49.029
they'll eventually notice us.

01:09:49.029 --> 01:09:52.340
Maybe to join the club, we
need to detect their signal.

01:09:52.340 --> 01:09:54.900
Maybe they don't
like getting in touch

01:09:54.900 --> 01:09:56.940
with too primitive
civilizations,

01:09:56.940 --> 01:10:00.010
and we haven't earned
our entrance ticket yet.

01:10:00.010 --> 01:10:03.332
But this is all
crazy speculation.

01:10:03.332 --> 01:10:05.290
You can speculate about
it, but if you actually

01:10:05.290 --> 01:10:07.748
want to make something happen,
you go look for the signals,

01:10:07.748 --> 01:10:10.440
and do it the best way you can.

01:10:10.440 --> 01:10:16.300
AUDIENCE: Hi, so how well can
you plausibly aim a laser?

01:10:16.300 --> 01:10:19.820
Right now, if we wanted to,
and NASA would shoot it up

01:10:19.820 --> 01:10:22.370
into space, or whatever we
were going to do with it,

01:10:22.370 --> 01:10:26.220
could we pick a star
at 70 light years,

01:10:26.220 --> 01:10:28.520
and say there is an
earth orbit around that,

01:10:28.520 --> 01:10:32.600
and we want to bathe that
orbit in light-- we could

01:10:32.600 --> 01:10:34.185
we hit that point in space?

01:10:34.185 --> 01:10:36.810
PAUL HOROWITZ: Yeah, actually it
was part of that nerd box that

01:10:36.810 --> 01:10:37.950
had a lot of stuff in there.

01:10:37.950 --> 01:10:39.700
Talked about the size--
you would actually

01:10:39.700 --> 01:10:41.370
would have to broaden it.

01:10:41.370 --> 01:10:46.490
The calculation I did was
for a 1-au target diameter

01:10:46.490 --> 01:10:48.840
at-- I forget what
the distance was, I

01:10:48.840 --> 01:10:51.590
think it was 1,000 light years.

01:10:51.590 --> 01:10:54.552
And that's diffraction limited
for the 10-meter telescope.

01:10:54.552 --> 01:10:56.260
If you want to spread
it out, because you

01:10:56.260 --> 01:10:58.593
think the planets might be
further out, you can do that,

01:10:58.593 --> 01:11:00.605
and it reduces the flux
by the square of the--

01:11:00.605 --> 01:11:01.521
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:11:01.521 --> 01:11:04.201
PAUL HOROWITZ: Yeah, well, not
going through the atmosphere,

01:11:04.201 --> 01:11:04.700
you can't.

01:11:04.700 --> 01:11:06.710
And so this would have
to be an orbital thing.

01:11:06.710 --> 01:11:08.918
And the question is, can
you do fractional arcsecond?

01:11:08.918 --> 01:11:11.520
You can do diffraction limited
with a 10-meter telescope.

01:11:11.520 --> 01:11:13.534
And we're going to
get better at that.

01:11:13.534 --> 01:11:15.450
I mean, it's really easy
in space-- everything

01:11:15.450 --> 01:11:16.590
is very quiet.

01:11:16.590 --> 01:11:18.840
There's no weather,
there's no wind,

01:11:18.840 --> 01:11:20.110
you don't get snow advisories.

01:11:22.589 --> 01:11:24.630
Or the backside of the
moon might be a good place

01:11:24.630 --> 01:11:27.340
to put a telescopes, you
know it's quiet there, too,

01:11:27.340 --> 01:11:29.220
and it shields you from
all the interference

01:11:29.220 --> 01:11:32.030
from Earth, if you want
to do that kind of thing.

01:11:32.030 --> 01:11:32.930
Another one?

01:11:32.930 --> 01:11:35.220
Yes.

01:11:35.220 --> 01:11:37.567
AUDIENCE: I've got a really
down to earth question.

01:11:37.567 --> 01:11:39.650
In the edition of your
book I have-- it's probably

01:11:39.650 --> 01:11:42.500
the second, if the third
one is the new one-- there's

01:11:42.500 --> 01:11:44.040
this wonderful
looking technology

01:11:44.040 --> 01:11:46.970
where you put these
sticky wires on a board,

01:11:46.970 --> 01:11:49.785
and you can prototype your
thing without a circuit mill,

01:11:49.785 --> 01:11:51.230
or without any chemicals.

01:11:51.230 --> 01:11:52.880
And that disappeared.

01:11:52.880 --> 01:11:54.312
Do you know why?

01:11:54.312 --> 01:11:56.770
PAUL HOROWITZ: Gee, I remember--
I had forgotten completely

01:11:56.770 --> 01:11:58.854
about that.

01:11:58.854 --> 01:12:00.270
AUDIENCE: A
Kollmorgen multi-wire.

01:12:00.270 --> 01:12:01.940
PAUL HOROWITZ: Yeah,
so what it did was,

01:12:01.940 --> 01:12:05.380
it was basically an alternative
to the PCBs, or wire wrap.

01:12:05.380 --> 01:12:08.740
And what it did was it just spit
out a sticky, inflated wire,

01:12:08.740 --> 01:12:10.590
they could cross
over each other.

01:12:10.590 --> 01:12:15.132
I remember, I got a board for
a nova that was a video board,

01:12:15.132 --> 01:12:16.590
and it was made by
a local company,

01:12:16.590 --> 01:12:17.880
and they did it with the system.

01:12:17.880 --> 01:12:19.410
And they went around, and
when it got to the pad

01:12:19.410 --> 01:12:20.640
that it was supposed
to go to-- everything

01:12:20.640 --> 01:12:22.910
was through hole in those
days, it actually just made

01:12:22.910 --> 01:12:24.550
a welded spot-- and
so the wires could

01:12:24.550 --> 01:12:26.160
cross with reckless abandon.

01:12:26.160 --> 01:12:28.540
You didn't need multiple
layers or anything else.

01:12:28.540 --> 01:12:29.750
Why did it disappear?

01:12:29.750 --> 01:12:32.090
It's probably a crappy way
to make more than one board

01:12:32.090 --> 01:12:35.490
of anything, and etch boards
are much more effective--

01:12:35.490 --> 01:12:36.826
particularly a multi-layer.

01:12:36.826 --> 01:12:38.700
I don't know-- wire-wrap
kind of disappeared.

01:12:38.700 --> 01:12:40.401
AUDIENCE: The problem was the
pulling from the [INAUDIBLE]

01:12:40.401 --> 01:12:40.890
if you flexed them.

01:12:40.890 --> 01:12:41.787
PAUL HOROWITZ: Is that right?

01:12:41.787 --> 01:12:43.162
AUDIENCE: I heard
that somewhere.

01:12:43.162 --> 01:12:44.820
PAUL HOROWITZ: So
don't flex them.

01:12:44.820 --> 01:12:46.360
AUDIENCE: You had to have
board stiffeners on it.

01:12:46.360 --> 01:12:47.750
PAUL HOROWITZ: I mean,
who would ever think

01:12:47.750 --> 01:12:48.999
that surface mount could work?

01:12:48.999 --> 01:12:50.661
You have these
little ceramic chips,

01:12:50.661 --> 01:12:52.160
and you're soldering
both ends down.

01:12:52.160 --> 01:12:55.970
And now it's on a board, and
you go like that, why don't they

01:12:55.970 --> 01:12:59.150
just all pop off?

01:12:59.150 --> 01:13:01.119
You know when you shove
the heat sink down,

01:13:01.119 --> 01:13:02.910
when you stick the CPU
on your motherboard,

01:13:02.910 --> 01:13:04.150
and then you push
that thing down,

01:13:04.150 --> 01:13:06.760
and it's supposed to snap in,
and the board goes like that?

01:13:06.760 --> 01:13:08.180
And you know it's all
full of these little--

01:13:08.180 --> 01:13:09.250
why don't they all just
[MAKING EXPLOSION SOUND]

01:13:09.250 --> 01:13:11.000
like that, and fly into the air?

01:13:11.000 --> 01:13:13.755
They don't, but
it shouldn't work.

01:13:13.755 --> 01:13:15.120
[LAUGHTER]

01:13:15.120 --> 01:13:16.800
Jim Williams, at
Linear Technology,

01:13:16.800 --> 01:13:18.510
used to say all the things
that shouldn't work.

01:13:18.510 --> 01:13:19.843
He says, disc brakes can't work.

01:13:19.843 --> 01:13:22.330
He said, ball point pen,
I would've fired that guy.

01:13:24.999 --> 01:13:26.540
So you can make
things work, you just

01:13:26.540 --> 01:13:28.932
have to work hard
to make them work.

01:13:28.932 --> 01:13:31.140
AUDIENCE: A theme that
recurred throughout the course

01:13:31.140 --> 01:13:34.881
or your talk was the advances
in technology over time.

01:13:34.881 --> 01:13:36.380
And corresponding
with that, there's

01:13:36.380 --> 01:13:38.770
also a decrease in the cost
for any given unit of, say,

01:13:38.770 --> 01:13:40.540
computing power over time.

01:13:40.540 --> 01:13:42.520
And something I thought
was really cool that

01:13:42.520 --> 01:13:46.437
happened a year or so ago,
was the IS EE3 reboot project,

01:13:46.437 --> 01:13:48.020
where a bunch of
guys in Mountain View

01:13:48.020 --> 01:13:50.330
took over McDonald's, and
took over a NASA probe,

01:13:50.330 --> 01:13:52.144
and tried to adjust
its orbit, and so on.

01:13:52.144 --> 01:13:54.560
And they failed, because there
was no pressure [INAUDIBLE]

01:13:54.560 --> 01:13:58.860
in the fuel tank for the thing--
but this ideas of reclaiming

01:13:58.860 --> 01:14:00.960
old technology at
the individual level.

01:14:00.960 --> 01:14:04.595
And now I'm kind of wondering
what your thoughts are on,

01:14:04.595 --> 01:14:06.220
at the individual
level, somebody who's

01:14:06.220 --> 01:14:08.320
interested in the stuff,
going into their basement

01:14:08.320 --> 01:14:11.860
and building a device with
the same computational power--

01:14:11.860 --> 01:14:14.820
the meta array that you guys
built in the '70s and '80s--

01:14:14.820 --> 01:14:16.950
and trying to do the same
experiments you guys were

01:14:16.950 --> 01:14:17.180
doing.

01:14:17.180 --> 01:14:18.305
Is there any merit to that?

01:14:18.305 --> 01:14:20.930
Does that add scientific value?

01:14:20.930 --> 01:14:22.670
PAUL HOROWITZ:
Yeah, interesting.

01:14:22.670 --> 01:14:24.640
So this big supernova
that was just

01:14:24.640 --> 01:14:26.730
discovered this
week, or last week,

01:14:26.730 --> 01:14:29.620
was found with a bunch of
automated small telescopes,

01:14:29.620 --> 01:14:31.660
that's run with a
small consortium.

01:14:31.660 --> 01:14:34.650
And there's nothing there
that's beyond amateur status,

01:14:34.650 --> 01:14:37.910
in particular-- by amateur,
I don't mean not smart,

01:14:37.910 --> 01:14:39.590
I mean doing it for the love.

01:14:39.590 --> 01:14:41.190
That's where the
word comes from.

01:14:41.190 --> 01:14:42.815
You can do an awful
lot of computation,

01:14:42.815 --> 01:14:44.290
and as that graph
showed about how

01:14:44.290 --> 01:14:46.835
you build your big
telescopes, the computations

01:14:46.835 --> 01:14:49.210
is where it's at if you have
a bunch of small telescopes.

01:14:49.210 --> 01:14:51.210
And you can do amazing things.

01:14:51.210 --> 01:14:53.720
So I think that amateur
astronomers are definitely

01:14:53.720 --> 01:14:56.280
in play, particularly when
the phase space that you have

01:14:56.280 --> 01:14:59.300
to explore is the whole sky,
and most of these projects

01:14:59.300 --> 01:15:02.010
are looking through soda
straws at particular places.

01:15:02.010 --> 01:15:03.760
I think there's
definite chances.

01:15:03.760 --> 01:15:06.741
In fact, you might say, why
aren't these signals strong?

01:15:06.741 --> 01:15:08.490
Given that even now,
we could make signals

01:15:08.490 --> 01:15:09.800
that are quite detectable.

01:15:09.800 --> 01:15:13.860
We can make a CW laser
at 100 megawatts,

01:15:13.860 --> 01:15:16.070
diffraction limited, is
much brighter than a star.

01:15:16.070 --> 01:15:17.570
It would be a
spectral [INAUDIBLE]--

01:15:17.570 --> 01:15:19.900
a star would turn
suddenly green or blue.

01:15:19.900 --> 01:15:21.765
Why don't we see those things?

01:15:21.765 --> 01:15:23.140
Well, probably
because they don't

01:15:23.140 --> 01:15:26.287
need to go that much overboard
to bring a new civilization in.

01:15:26.287 --> 01:15:28.620
But if they're interested in
bringing a new civilization

01:15:28.620 --> 01:15:32.520
in before we blow ourselves
up, or elect a really

01:15:32.520 --> 01:15:36.450
untenable president,
then it may pay for them

01:15:36.450 --> 01:15:37.710
to send pretty strong signals.

01:15:37.710 --> 01:15:41.244
In which case, I think
one-meter class telescopes,

01:15:41.244 --> 01:15:42.660
or robotic telescopes
on which you

01:15:42.660 --> 01:15:45.760
can drive some stream of data
from it, or these data streams

01:15:45.760 --> 01:15:47.640
can be split and provided
to multiple users,

01:15:47.640 --> 01:15:50.290
I think it's definitely
a thing to do.

01:15:50.290 --> 01:15:55.066
And with the availability
of cheap GPUs, and FPGAs,

01:15:55.066 --> 01:15:56.940
and boards that do all
this stuff-- you know,

01:15:56.940 --> 01:15:58.940
the Adafruit and SparkFunds
of the world, really

01:15:58.940 --> 01:16:00.210
make this easy stuff.

01:16:00.210 --> 01:16:04.722
So I say go for it,
and report back.

01:16:04.722 --> 01:16:07.180
AUDIENCE: I remember there was
a SETI at Home program, that

01:16:07.180 --> 01:16:10.440
would take spare compute cycles
and go off and look at signals.

01:16:10.440 --> 01:16:11.404
Is that still ongoing?

01:16:11.404 --> 01:16:13.820
PAUL HOROWITZ: Yeah, in fact
SETI at Home, so SETI at HOME

01:16:13.820 --> 01:16:15.730
is run out of Berkeley
by the same folks

01:16:15.730 --> 01:16:17.890
who bring you this Casper
project and the FPGAs

01:16:17.890 --> 01:16:18.710
that I showed you.

01:16:18.710 --> 01:16:22.880
And SETI at home takes data
from the Arecibo telescope.

01:16:22.880 --> 01:16:24.520
The Arecibo telescope
is this dish

01:16:24.520 --> 01:16:25.850
with the thing sticking down.

01:16:25.850 --> 01:16:28.960
And because they want to keep
pointing at the same thing,

01:16:28.960 --> 01:16:31.420
the feed has to move, so
the thing swivels around

01:16:31.420 --> 01:16:33.350
and goes in and out.

01:16:33.350 --> 01:16:35.760
And other feed isn't
doing anything--

01:16:35.760 --> 01:16:36.940
it's doing curlicues.

01:16:36.940 --> 01:16:39.490
So SETI at Home took data
from the curlicue feed

01:16:39.490 --> 01:16:41.804
that nobody wanted, and
basically parsed it up

01:16:41.804 --> 01:16:43.470
and sent it all the
way out to everybody

01:16:43.470 --> 01:16:44.780
to run on their things.

01:16:44.780 --> 01:16:48.155
And there's wonderful maps of
the sky, as curlicued with SETI

01:16:48.155 --> 01:16:49.260
at Home.

01:16:49.260 --> 01:16:50.560
That's alive and well.

01:16:50.560 --> 01:16:53.080
And in fact, this new
project Breakthrough

01:16:53.080 --> 01:16:55.280
is going to make
public all of its data

01:16:55.280 --> 01:16:59.440
in some form that's actually
usable-- not the full 320

01:16:59.440 --> 01:17:03.160
gigabits per second, but some
cleaned up version of that.

01:17:03.160 --> 01:17:07.230
Part of their mandate is
not to sit on this data.

01:17:07.230 --> 01:17:09.320
The same way Kepler
data is made public,

01:17:09.320 --> 01:17:13.410
and the public Genome Project
published their stuff, too.

01:17:13.410 --> 01:17:16.400
So if what you want
to do is software

01:17:16.400 --> 01:17:19.485
on someone else's data, you'll
have more than you can handle.

01:17:19.485 --> 01:17:21.360
And I don't know if
that's going to be turned

01:17:21.360 --> 01:17:22.990
into-- I see flashing lights.

01:17:22.990 --> 01:17:26.060
That could be a laser pulse
from alien intelligence,

01:17:26.060 --> 01:17:29.490
or it could be a sign that
I'm supposed to stop talking.

01:17:29.490 --> 01:17:31.080
I think the latter.

01:17:31.080 --> 01:17:32.580
Thank you.

01:17:32.580 --> 01:17:35.030
[APPLAUSE]

